<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Inflation Drops in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's inflation
rate dropped from 8 percent in September to a 14-month low of 7.5
percent in October this year, the Central Statistics Service
(CSS) announced today.
</P>
<P>
The rate was only 0.1 percentage point higher than in August
1996.
</P>
<P>
The monthly increase of the consumer price index (CPI), as
well as the increase in the seasonally adjusted index, was 0.4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The CPI increase was mainly due to price hikes in food,
housing and transport with each contributing to 0.1 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The price index for food showed an annual growth rate of 6.8
percent in October, 1.5 percentage points lower than the 8.3
percent in September.
</P>
<P>
It registered a monthly increase of 0.8 percent, also lower
than the corresponding rate of 2.2 percent in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although inflation was easing, South Africa's economy slowed
down significantly in the third quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
According to CSS figures released on Tuesday, South Africa's
GDP growth nose-dived to only 0.3 percent in the third quarter,
compared with the 2.4 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The decline was attributed to bad behavior in most of the
economic sectors, especially in manufacturing, electricity, gas
and water, and construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
