<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Doubts Credibility of Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that the latest Israeli redeployment proposal is
"neither adequately serious nor credible to be feasible for
salvaging the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remarks after a meeting with his visiting French
counterpart Hubert Vedrine who also held talks with President
Hosni Mubarak on the Mideast peace process, the U.N.-Iraq crisis
and bilateral relations during his short visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's remarks came in response to a proposal reportedly put
forward by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on offering
the Palestinian National Authority 6-8 percent of the West Bank
area now under sole Israeli control in further pullbacks as
stipulated in the Hebron agreement signed in January.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Vedrine said the peace process needs practical
proposals to get it moving again.
</P>
<P>
"Our worries are identical vis-a-vis the grave crisis in the
Middle East peace march," he said. "We, once again, evaluated all
our drives in this domain to see how to reactivate the process,"
Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
All the world at present are preoccupied with the peace
process, including, in particular, Egypt, France, the EU, the U.S.
and some people in Israel, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All have agreed that what is needed is an even-handed
political solution that stems from the commitments already
pledged," he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Vedrine will also meet with Arab League
Secretary General Ahmed Abdel-Meguid to discuss the European role
in the Middle East peace process and means of promoting Euro-Arab
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine's three-day Mideast tour has so far taken him to Israel
and the Palestinian self-rule area. He will complete his mission
with another tour, scheduled to begin on January 12 next year,
which will include visits to Syria, Lebanon and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister had prepared for his visit through
intensified consultations with his European partners in Luxembourg
last weekend. He also contacted his U.S., Russian, German and
British counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
