<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Proceed with Farm Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe said here today the acquisition of farms for resettlement
would proceed with or without the assistance of the British
government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a two-hour meeting with Nick
Swanepoel and David Husluck, president and director of the
Commercial Farmers Union respectively, Mugabe said the colonial
exercise would be corrected once and for all.
</P>
<P>
The government had not gone to Britain to beg for money but to
tell the British that the land question had not been resolved at
the Lancaster house talks in 1979 and had nearly brought a
dead-lock to the talks which result in Zimbabwe's independence in
1980, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I insisted that our team which was going to negotiate make it
clear there was no way we could go back to accepting a
willing-seller settlement or accept to pay compensation to
farmers for the purchase of the land. We are only prepared to
pay for improvements on the land," the president noted.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he had briefed the farmers on the land issue and
gave them the background which included setting up the machinery
for assessing the land at provincial and national level.
</P>
<P>
A list of 1,503 farms identified for designation would be
gazetted on Friday, Mugabe said, adding that the government was
willing to listen to ideas and incorporate them into the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said they had expressed to the president farmers'
concerns over the land issue which included the criteria followed
in the designation of farms.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not elaborate on the concerns, saying he would
comment after the list had been gazetted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
