<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. GDP Maintain Robust Growth in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Strong consumer spending
and the active business investment in equipment in nearly 14 years
pushed economic growth to a robust 3.3 percent annual rate, the
Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The third quarter's expansion was achieved with little
inflation. A price measure linked to GDP inched up at a 1.5
percent annual rate, the smallest increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Labor Department reported that the number
of first-time claims for unemployment benefits dropped by 31,000
to 303,000 last week. It was the sharpest decrease since early
August.
</P>
<P>
The latest quarterly economic growth marks a slight downward
revision from the 3.5 percent estimated a month ago. The
department attributed the change to somewhat weaker export growth,
slower growth in commercial construction and a diminished rate of
inventory accumulation.
</P>
<P>
In October, orders to factories for durable goods fell 0.3
percent to a seasonally adjusted 185.9 billion U. S. dollars after
advancing only 0.1 percent in September, the Commerce Department
said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first drop since May. However, purchases of durable
goods by consumers and businesses were the driving force in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending overall rose at a 5.8 percent annual rate,
the fastest pace in about 5 years. Americans' purchases of durable
goods, items from cars to computers, shot up at an 18.2 percent
pace, the best in about 9 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, business spending on equipment from trucks to
turbines soared at a 24.1 percent rate, the best since the final
three months of 1983.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction rose at a 3.7 percent rate and
government spending at a 1.1 percent pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
