<HEADLINE> Pakistan Court to Hear Petition Against 13th Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of
Pakistan will continue to hear a petition challenging the 13th
Amendment to the Constitution on Thursday, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment, which was passed by the Parliament in April
this year, took away the powers of the President to dissolve the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, a five-member bench headed by Chief Justice of the
court, Sajjad Ali Shah, heard the arguments of the petitioner's
counsel and decided to hear the petition again on November 27.
</P>
<P>
If the Supreme Court upholds the petition against the 13th
Amendment, a controversial article in the constitution, under
which the President has the powers to dissolve the National
Assembly, will be restored, according to the sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
