<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho AIDS Cases to Rise to 40,000 in Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 26 (Xinhua) -- There will be one AIDS
patient in every 50 Lesotho citizens in four years, South African
Press Association quoted a Lesotho report as saying today.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 people will have full blown AIDS (acquired
immuno-deficiency syndrome) in Lesotho in four years time, the
Lesotho National AIDS Prevention and Control Program said in a
report released to coincide with the commemoration of World AIDS
Day next Monday.
</P>
<P>
It warned that the epidemic could have potential devastating
consequences on the country's economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho government is expected to adopt a multi-sectoral
approach to combat the fatal disease. This will include more
participation by the public and private sectors, non-governmental
organizations, institutes of higher learning and the donor
community, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics in the report, AIDS cases rose to
2,400 by mid-1997. The number of new cases reported countrywide
reached the highest annual figure of 936 last year.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's capital, Maseru, had the highest prevalence rate,
with 43 percent of HIV-infected women found there.
</P>
<P>
The HIV (human immuno-deficiency virus) virus leads to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Young people in the 20 to 39 age group were the most
susceptible to the disease, the statistics showed. These
constituted 65 percent of reported cases. Women patients
dominated this age group while male patients dominated the 40 to
59 years age group.
</P>
<P>
The number of children orphaned as a result of the disease
also increased.
</P>
<P>
The report also attributed the quick spread of the disease to
migrant labor.
</P>
<P>
The movement of most Lasotho men to South Africa in search for
jobs increased the risk, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Rural to urban migrations within Lesotho led to high
concentrations of predominantly male communities and increased
the prevalence of commercial sex in urban areas, thus
accelerating the spread of HIV virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
