<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coup-Attempt Trial in Qatar Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 26 (Xinhua) -- A trial held by Qatar today
on 110 people accused of involvement in a foiled coup attempt in
1996 has been adjourned to next year, said reports reaching here
from Doha.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters, Abudullah Yousuf al Mal,
prosecutor general of the Qatari Supreme Court said the trial will
be postponed to "February 11 next year to enable laywers to study
trial-related files and consider requested evidence."
</P>
<P>
The court made the decision after defenders asked for a
postponement to read the files. Seventy defendants appeared in
court today, while 40 others, including former interior minister
Hamad bin Jassem al-Thani, are being tried in absentia.
</P>
<P>
The defendants have been charged with treason for involvement
in the coup against Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani, who
toppled his father in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Defendants grumbled during today's trial that the court did not
allow them to see their lawyers and relatives when they were
prisoned, al Mal said.
</P>
<P>
He also told reporters that those defendants who were absent
from today's session will be informed by the police of the
countries in which they are living.
</P>
<P>
If they keep absent during next year's trial, they will be
judged by default, he said. Two Egyptians and one Bahraini are
being tried in absentia.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has said the two Egyptians, Attiya Badri and Ahmed Tawfic
Said were from the Egyptian army and some Qatari officials,
including the Qatari Foreign Minister Hamad Bin Jassim Jabir
al-Thani made comments implicating Cairo in the failed coup
attempt.
</P>
<P>
Egypt denied the charges. Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said that the two Egyptian suspects are "retired army officers
who had temporary work contract with the Qatari government."
</P>
<P>
Egypt also called on Qatar to clarify its position towards the
charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
