<HEADLINE> Reshuffles Won't Change Economic Course, Says Nemtsov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The latest changes in
government posts will not influence Russia's economic course, said
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov today.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov told a press conference that the course aimed at the
intensive work of improving Russia's economy. It remained and
nobody is likely to change it, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Practically all the ministers have retained their posts. So
have the first deputy prime ministers and the prime minister," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov described the newly-appointed Finance Minister Mikhail
Zadornov as a very progressive person oriented toward faster
financial stabilization.
</P>
<P>
The first deputy premier said some activists who want to
reverse the movement will not succeed.
</P>
<P>
Another report quoted Alexander Shokhin, the first deputy
speaker of the State Duma, as saying that the possibility of
another wave of government reshuffles still exists.
</P>
<P>
Shokhin said tax collecting bodies might be affected by
mistakes made by the Finance Ministry and the State Taxation
Service in tax collection. 
</P>
