<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Publishes Report of EU's Trade Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's single
market program and liberalization under the World Trade
Organization (WTO) have generally improved access conditions for
the EU's trading partners and increased exposure of the EU economy
to international competition and structural change, WTO stated in
its report on the EU's trade policies and practices published here
today.
</P>
<P>
However, despite progressive liberalization, there are still
significant internal obstacles to efficient resource allocation,
resulting in higher costs in some industrial and services sectors
with adverse consequences on growth and competitiveness, the
report points out.
</P>
<P>
The report covers changes since the last Trade Policy Review,
held in 1995. The report prepared by the WTO secretariat, along
with a policy statement prepared by the EU itself, provides the
basis for a review of the EU's trade policies and practices in the
WTO Trade Policy Review Body on November 25-26.
</P>
<P>
The WTO report concludes that the EU's trade policies and
practices have generally evolved in a favorable direction.
</P>
<P>
This should benefit both the EU and its trading partners, the
report says, adding at the same time that the present transitional
period in European economic integration presents challenges both
for the EU and the multilateral trading system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
