<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Impasse Continues in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The political standoff
between India's Congress party and the ruling United Front
continued when the former decided tonight to send one more letter
to Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral instead of withdrawing
support to the minority government.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India, the decision was made by
the Congress Working Committee, the supreme decision-making body
of the Congress party, which met here tonight to discuss moves on
the current political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered last week following the release of an
investigative report which accused the Dravida Munnetra Kazagham
(DMK), a major constituent of the ruling United Front, of being
linked with the assassination of former prime minister Rajiv
Gandhi in 1991.
</P>
<P>
After the report was tabled in the parliament last Thursday,
Congress party President Sitaram Kesri wrote to Prime Minister
Gujral demanding the removal of three DMK ministers from the
government.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the Congress party will otherwise withdraw its
crucial support to the minority government.
</P>
<P>
In a reply to Kesri on Monday, however, Gujral rejected the
Congress' demand but agreed to talk with the party on the issue.
</P>
<P>
At its meeting held here tonight, the Congress Working
Committee apparently did not approve immediate withdrawal of
support to the 13-party United Front government.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the two-hour meeting, Congress party spokesman
V.N. Gadgil told reporters that a letter is being sent tonight to
Prime Minister Gujral in response to his letter rejecting the
Congress party's demand for sacking the three DMK ministers.
</P>
<P>
"The content of the letter is confidential," the spokesman
said, declining to elaborate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
