<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Continues to Fall Despite Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee continued
to slide against the U.S. dollar today touching 38.72 in intra-day
trading before the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) intervened with
massive dollar selling, helping it close at 38.54/60 rupees on
Bombay's foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
This is the third day in succession that the rupee has plunged
to an all-time low against the dollar, largely due to currency
speculators taking advantage of the continued turmoil in the
political scene of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India, for most of the day,
banks tested the RBI reference level of 38.56 and extensively
bought dollars in the wake of heavy corporate demand and offshore
fundings, sending the currency to its lowest-ever level of 38.72
at noon.
</P>
<P>
However, RBI's reported intervention of between 50 and 100
million dollars helped prop up the rupee in a volatile market
which expects the currency to decline further and trade at around
39.00 to the dollar tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign exchange dealers said the RBI may not let the
rupee, which has dropped almost eight percent in value since
September, decline any further, at least in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is said to have sold over 1.5 billion dollars
in the last two weeks to defend the currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
