<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Opposition Safina Party Registered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government
registered influential opposition Safina party today, 33 days
before the country's second multi-party general election set for
December 29.
</P>
<P>
This brought the total number of registered political parties
to 22 in the eastern African country, meaning its presidential
race may attract 22 contenders at most.
</P>
<P>
"The government has allowed the registration of all political
parties whose applications are pending with the Registrar of
Societies. This includes Safina," said a brief statement from the
Presidential Press Service (PPS).
</P>
<P>
However, the party's Secretary-General, Richard Leakey, told a
press conference today that the party has so far not decided
whether to take part in or still boycott the elections. The
decision is to be announced tomorrow, he added.
</P>
<P>
"While welcoming the news Safina has been granted
registration, we condemn in the strongest terms the
unconstitutional and undemocratic processes that occasioned the
delay," said Leakey.
</P>
<P>
Safina was denied registration on the grounds of posing
threats to "peace, welfare and good order in Kenya" at the
beginning of October when other 10 parties were registered.
</P>
<P>
"The delay in registration has clearly been a tactic by the
government to wrong-foot the pro-democracy movement and the last
minute decision to give us legitimacy in law is surely intended
to divide the opposition," Leakey claimed.
</P>
<P>
Safina, which means Noah's Ark in Swahili language, was set up
in June 1995 with the aim to unite opposition parties as many as
possible in an attempt to defeat President Daniel arap Moi in the
coming elections.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 74 and in power for 19 years, is the sole presidential
candidate of the ruling Kenya African National Union party and
widely believed to win the election for another five-year rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
