<HEADLINE> France Checks Boeing 747 Planes to Prevent Failure Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- All the Boeing 747 passenger
planes which are in service in France have been subjected to
technical checks, in order to prevent a technical failure similar
to the U.S. TWA 800 plane, said the French Minister of Transport
Jean-Claude Gayssot today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the authorities have been analyzing the
recommendations from the Federal Agency of Aviation (FAA) of the
United States, which is the authority to issue certificates to the
Boeing 747 jets.
</P>
<P>
A hythothesis on a technical failure in the central reservoir
was raised after the TWA 800 passenger plane exploded in Long
Island Coast, New York, on July 17, 1996, killing all 230 people
on board.
</P>
<P>
Recommended inspections of Boeing 747 planes were made
immediately obligatory to all French operators using the type of
plane and it has allowed the correction of some defaults, said the
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
