<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Stock Market Sets Up Standby Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced tonight that the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange (KLSE) has set up a standby fund of 500 million
ringgit (about 143 million U.S. dollars) in case any member
company needs help to reduce possible systemic risks in a currency
and stock market crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The KLSE committee has approved a KLSE/SCANS (Securities
Clearing Automated Network Services) standby fund," Anwar, who is
also finance minister, said at the KLSE annual dinner here.
</P>
<P>
He said the amount was decided after a thorough study.
</P>
<P>
As for the equity market, he said, the KLSE was monitoring on a
daily basis the financial position of all stockbroking companies,
including their exposure to clients.
</P>
<P>
There has been no default of payment to the clearing house by
any member company, Anwar said, adding that in fact four of these
companies had increased their paid-up capital to improve their
share-holders fund position and another two were making plans to
do so.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all those involved in securities industries to
identify new plans to revive current plans to satisfy their
clients' needs and provide sound continuity for themselves.
</P>
<P>
"Member companies must continue to perform their duty of
marketing our stocks. Our analyses must maintain their
objectivity. If they keep following the foreign herd and
downgrading Malaysian companies which are strong and stable, the
situation will take a longer time to improve," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said it was everyone's responsibility to see the nation
through this trying period.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would meet the challenge of restoring
confidence in the market by maintaining a sound financial system.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's currency and stock markets have been in a downward
trend since July when a currency crisis hit the Southeast Asian
region.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's currency -- the ringgit, today ended at 3.4920/20 to
the U.S. dollar, marginally higher against Tuesday's 3.4960 and
2.5200 in early July.
</P>
<P>
But the KLSE today closed sharply lower with further losses on
financial counters, in line with the weakening sentiment of
regional financial sectors following problems faced by Japan.
</P>
<P>
At today's close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index (CI)
fell 15.45 points to 526.12, the all-share Emas Index dropped
5.15 points to 142.36, the Second Board Index lost 8.00 points to
235.35 while the Industrial Index was 17.70 points lower at
1,066.52.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE's CI stood at over 1,000 points in early July this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
