<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriots to Organize Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Thirty Greek and Turkish
Cypriot organizations have initiated a first joint event "The
Festival for Peace" in an effort for rapprochement between the
two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
The event will be held Saturday at the Ledra Palace Hotel
in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today, Stephanos Stephanou,
representing the Greek Cypriot organizations involved in this
event, said "the festival comes at a time when military
activities and armaments are on the increase and increased
nationalism poses a grave danger for new conflicts and wars."
</P>
<P>
He called on everybody who backs efforts for rapprochement
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities, forcibly
separated since the 1974 Turkish invasion, to attend Saturday's
fiesta.
</P>
<P>
Cemal Ozit, representing the Turkish Cypriot organizations,
warned that another war on the island will leave all the
Cypriots "in tears."
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that neither the Turkish nor the Greek
Cypriots are responsible for the present situation on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Organizers told reporters that they had decided to set up a
permanent coordinating committee to promote common goals for
peace through joint meetings and various functions.
</P>
<P>
"Contact between us so far has convinced us that the two
communities have joint objectives, common fears and visions,"
they said.
</P>
<P>
The Saturday's event is expected to adopt a declaration
against war and for a common homeland.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over 37 percent of the island following a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
