<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Running on IMF Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government Tuesday
approved a second letter of intent outlining the country's
economic rehabilitation plans and pledging to continue to take
necessary measures to revive the economy with the aid of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The letter, which will be submitted to the IMF for review to
facilitate the transfer of the second tranche of its 17.2 billion
U.S. dollar aid package, included the new Thai government's policy
adjustments as well as new steps to keep Thailand running on the
track co-laid with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
In the revised letter of intent, the government led by Chuan
Leekpai, which was sworn in on November 15, reassessed Thailand's
key economic targets for 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
It admitted that Thailand now is facing some problems,
including the weakness in short-term macro-economic planning.
</P>
<P>
The slower return of confidence has further caused the baht to
depreciate, mounted pressure on interest rates and resulted in
sharper decline in private investments and consumption than
originally anticipated, the Thai finance ministry said on Tuesday
in a press release on the letter.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the new government adjusted Thailand's economic
growth targets set by the previous government of Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh, lowering them to 0.6 percent for this year and 0-1
percent for 1998 but slightly raising the inflation control
targets to 10 percent for 1997 and 6 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chuan government also unveiled concrete measures or
timetables for tackling major economic problems, especially those
facing the country's battered financial sector, and pledged to
push ahead with some plans of the previous government.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministry said the government has introduced fiscal
measures to trim the country's current account deficit as required
by the IMF, citing budget cuts and tax hikes for example.
</P>
<P>
On monetary policy, the ministry said the Thai central bank
will stick to a tight monetary stance and set interest rates
mainly with the objective to help stabilize the baht and restore
confidence in domestic financial assets.
</P>
<P>
The government will also act as quickly as possible to remove
the limits on the purchasing, selling and borrowing of baht by
non-residents, the ministry noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government set timetables and guidelines in
the letter for the Financial Restructuring Agency (FRA) and the
Asset Management Corporation (AMC) to work on bailing out 58
suspended finance firms and reinforcing other financial
institutions remaining in operation, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministry is set to decide by December 7 whether or
which of the 58 finance firms will reopen. It has set a timetable
to implement the measures announced by the previous government
last month for strengthening the existing healthy financial
institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
In other areas, privatization is one of the key medium-term
goals for the government and it will announce firm plans in the
area by June next year, including reduction of government stakes
in the national airline.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government is currently urging the IMF to review its
performance in the economic rehabilitation process after it
withdrew a tranche of 1.6 billion dollars from the IMF in August
this year.
</P>
<P>
It is also asking the IMF to transfer its second tranche of aid
as soon as possible to prop up its falling foreign exchange
reserves and the falling baht.
</P>
<P>
The baht has depreciated to some 40 baht to the U.S. dollar in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
IMF chief Michel Camdessus said in Washington on Tuesday that
he gave full endorsement of the latest letter submitted by
Thailand and asked the IMF's executive board to consider extending
the second tranche of its aid to Thailand after reviewing the
letter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-26 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies Allegations of Spying on UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today denied allegations
that it is spying on contacts and the activities of the U.N.
Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating weapons of
mass destruction in Iraq, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was in no need of spying on UNSCOM contacts or activities
because Iraq had no proscribed weapons or materials to conceal
before the U.N. inspection teams, the agency quoted an official
spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times carried an article Tuesday, which quoted a
UNSCOM spokesman as saying that Iraq is spying on UNSCOM contacts
or activities.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that Iraq had opened the doors for
the UNSCOM to inspect Iraqi factories, installations and
laboratories and fully cooperated with the commission within its
fulfillment of obligations toward relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM spokesman and those who support him in Washington
such as U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen "who has a hand in
raising the same charges, are well aware that their charges fall
short of evidence," the Iraqi spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Cohen issued a statement recently, saying that Iraqi
authorities had obstructed U.N. weapons inspectors' access to some
suspected sites in Iraq. Iraq has denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
"If those charges were true," said the spokesman, "They would
be raised before Iraqi authorities and even the U.N. Security
Council."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the UNSCOM spokesman's claim that by spying on
UNSCOM contacts, Iraq authorities would know the sites that the
UNSCOM intended to inspect and conceal proscribed weapons before
U.N. monitoring teams arrived, the Iraqi spokesman said for many
times, heads of many inspection teams had informed the Iraqi
authorities that they only had an idea of the sites they intended
to inspect only a few minutes before the teams headed for the
sites.
</P>
<P>
"How can the Iraqi authorities be aware of the sites before
the inspectors themselves?" the spokesman asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Uzbek Warlord Sends Peace Mission to Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ethnic-Uzbek
warlord Rashid Dostum today sent a delegation to the headquarters
of the Islamic Taliban militia in Kandahar apparently to discuss a
peaceful end to the country's on-going bitter fighting.
</P>
<P>
"This meeting is very important to end the current crisis in
Afghanistan," said a Taliban spokesman in Kandahar, Taliban's
stronghold in southern Afghanistan, according to a report
monitored here this evening.
</P>
<P>
However, neither Dostum nor the Taliban spokesman could
immediately be reached for comment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It's not clear what prompted today's meeting, but the Taliban
spokesman said the Taliban will be sending its representatives to
the opposition's stronghold of Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north
of the Afghan capital of Kabul, in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
"We are hopeful through these kinds of contacts with other
factions as well that we will be able to solve Afghanistan's
problems through negotiations," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, who is part of the anti-Taliban northern alliance
locked in a protracted battle with the Taliban, has stepped out on
his own in recent weeks exchanging prisoners with the Taliban
militia and offering to return the bodies of Taliban fighters
allegedly massacred in northern Afghanistan last May.
</P>
<P>
However, there have been no signs that other members of the
northern alliance, including Afghanistan's former military chief
Ahmad Masood, were willing to negotiate with the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday several senior Taliban leaders, including the former
governor of western Herat Abdul Razzak, arrived in Kandahar after
spending seven months in prison in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Dostum may have arranged their freedom
after sending his former ally, Abdul Malik, fleeing abroad.
</P>
<P>
Malik arrested thousands of Taliban fighters last May,
including Razzak, after a deal he had struck with them soured.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban control roughly 85 percent of Afghanistan, imposing
its brand of Islamic rule on the area. The northern 15 percent is
run by the anti-Taliban alliance, made up mostly of the country's
minority ethnic and religious groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
