<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 90 Buildings Damaged in Indonesia's Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 26 (Xinhua) -- At least 90 buildings
including houses, mosques and offices in Gorontalo district of
Indonesia's North Sulawesi province, were damaged by an earthquake
which, measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale, hit the area on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
No casualties have been reported in the quake, believed to be
the second largest in magnitude to hit North Sulawesi in the last
seven years, the Antara News Agency quoted a local official as
saying today.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake, which occurred at 19:14 p.m. local
time, was 78 km to the northwest of Gorontalo.
</P>
<P>
"After the first quake, there were some continued small
aftershocks," an official said. "It affected surrounding areas in
Kotamobagu, Bolaang Mongondow and Minahasa districts, and Manado,
capital of the North Sulawesi province," he said.
</P>
<P>
The strongest quake to hit the region was on June 20, 1991,
which measured 6.9 on the Richter scale and destroyed 1,500
buildings in Gorontalo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
