<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Children Suffer from Malnutrition: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one million
children in Southern and Central Iraq are chronically
malnourished, according to survey results published here today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted jointly by the Iraqi Government and the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), found that 32 percent of
children under the age of five in the areas suffer from
malnutrition, a rise of 72 percent over 1991.
</P>
<P>
About 23 percent are found underweight, twice as high as the
levels found in neighboring Jordan and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
There has been no sign of improvement since the U.N. Security
Council resolution on oil-for-food came into effect in December
1996, says Philippe Heffinck, UNICEF Representative in Baghdad.
</P>
</TEXT>
