<HEADLINE> COMESA to Establish Free Agricultural Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) said here
today that the regional body plans to establish a free trade area
in agricultural products by 1999, the Zambia News Agency ZANA
reported today.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted the COMESA official Erastus Mwencha as saying when
opening a two-day COMESA round-table conference on commodity
development in eastern and southern Africa that a free trade area
in agriculture by 1999 will enable the reginal body attain free
trade in the year 2000 for all products.
</P>
<P>
The compelling factor for this action is "to legitimise cross
border informal trade in agricultural produce, expand the market
for farmers in the region and promote the attainment of food
security for the region given the complimentarity of agricultural
seasons in easten and southern africa", said Mwencha.
</P>
<P>
He, however, cautioned that other issues like increased
production of agricultural commodities have to be addressed in
COMESA countries if trade in agricultural commodities has to be
sustained.
</P>
<P>
It should be remembered that the expansion of agricultural
trade among the COMESA countries depends to a large extent on the
timely and cost effective supply of agricultural inputs, such as
fertilisers, improved seeds, pesticides, agricultural machinery,
tools, spare parts and fuel, Mwencha noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that producer prices and marketing efficiency of
agricultural commodities have also to be addressed so that
increased productivity in agriculture could be achieved among the
20 COMESA member states which aim to establish a free trade area
by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
