<HEADLINE> Derelict Luxor Policemen Face Trial in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Interior Minister Habib
Ibrahim el-Adli has issued a decision to refer to trial before the
Higher Police Disciplinary Council a number of senior police
officers for dereliction of duty in the Luxor massacre.
</P>
<P>
The former director of the general administration of Luxor
police and his deputy as well as other four officers will be tried
on charges of negligence in carrying out security plans for
securing archaeological and tourist areas in Luxor, said Egypt's
Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The decisions were taken following investigations by the
Inspection and Control Sector of the Interior Ministry into the
November 17 terrorist attack in Egypt's biggest archeological city.
</P>
<P>
Six Islamic militants went on a shooting spree, killing 58
foreign tourists and four Egyptians in front of a Pharaonic temple
in Luxor before they were gunned down by the police who were slow
to the rescue. The area around the temple was guarded by only two
policemen.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, Egypt has replaced its top security chief,
kicked out a number of senior police officers and revamped its
security plans.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa will fly
to Zurich Friday to attend an official funeral arranged by the
Swiss government for its nationals killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti flew here a day after the
massacre which claimed about 35 Swiss holiday-makers
alone. Switzerland has warned travelers to stay away from Egypt
altogether as Swiss travel agents reported cancellations flooding
in.
</P>
<P>
Since Islamic militants began to wage a war against the
government in 1992, nearly 1,300 people have been killed, mostly
policemen and militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
