<HEADLINE> People's Daily: Promoting Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Jiang put forward important and constructive
proposals on adhering to "the APEC Approach" and further
strengthening economic cooperation of the region, the editorial
says.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that economic and technological cooperation and
trade and investment liberalization are closely linked and should
support each other. Science and technology cooperation should be
an important part and priority area in the region's economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also spoke in detail about fully opening the market for
technology trade, encouraging and speeding up the transfer of
hi-technologies to all members and developing members in
particular and rationalizing the intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
These far-reaching views were highly valued at the meeting and
reflected in the Vancouver Declaration, the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang proposed that APEC make an agenda for science
and technology industry cooperation into the 21 century. Member
leaders all accepted this proposal and instructed their ministers
to work out a draft agenda and report to the next year's meeting
in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang also expounded Chinese position on sustainable
development. APEC should devote itself to pushing forward the
economic development of all its members if it wants to maintain
the ever lasting vigor of the region.
</P>
<P>
"But the reality is that there is a great divergency in terms
of economy and technology development among the APEC members," the
editorial say.
</P>
<P>
"Thus how to create favorable conditions for the
developing members, how will the developed members use their
economic and technological advantages to help the developing
ones, and how to enhance science and technology cooperation and
technology transfer among the members become big questions
relating to the future of the region's economic cooperation and
development," the editorial adds.
</P>
<P>
The economic prosperity of the developing members and the
improvement of the living standard of their people will also
create more spaces for the economic sustainable development of
their developed counterparts and inject more driving force for the
regional economic cooperation, it says.
</P>
<P>
In a world that all countries are now more
economically interrelated, the economic development of the
developing countries is the real hope of realizing global economic
sustainable development, the editorial points out.
</P>
</TEXT>
