<HEADLINE> Malaria Remains Nigeria's No. 1 Killer Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaria remains the major killer
disease in Nigeria, sending some 300,000 Nigerians to the grave
annually, a medical expert said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to Lateef Salako, Director-General of the Nigerian
Institute for Medical Research, 64 million persons in the country are
infected by malaria parasite yearly, while 50 million actually
suffered the disease, especially women and children.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a population of around 100 million.
</P>
<P>
Malaria parasite, discovered 100 years ago, was becoming resistant
to common drugs as well as to various brands of insecticides, he said
at a health seminar.
</P>
<P>
The professor said that the endemic disease in the country is
worsening poverty, saying that "there is a lack of commitment on the
part of government to eradicate the disease".
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to adopt preventive measures to tackle the
malaria problem.
</P>
<P>
Hussain Abdulkarim, President of the Malaria Care Organization
in Africa, also claimed a lack of serious commitment by the
international community to eradicate malaria in the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
He commended the federal ministry of health for introducing
insecticide-treated nets as a way of combating malaria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
