<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-26 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon: Syrian Troops to Stay Until Israelis Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berry said today that the presence of Syrian troops in Lebanon is
aimed at liberating the south from Israeli occupation and will
stay until Israelis pull out.
</P>
<P>
"Syrian troops will withdraw from Lebanon only when the legal
Lebanese government and organizations require them to do so," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when answering a question at a news
conference held for some 70 journalists from 40 countries who are
attending the World Christian Journalism Conference here.
</P>
<P>
Berry said that the 40,000 Syrian soldiers now stationing in
Lebanon were invited by the Lebanese authority. They do not take a
single cent from Lebanon, but also help Lebanon restore its unity
and safety.
</P>
<P>
When Israel pulls its troops out of Lebanon, then the
discussion about Syrian troops withdrawal will start, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Syrian troops do not fight with Israeli soldiers
in the south because no permission is given by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Syrian troops officially entered Lebanon in 1976 as major part
of a 30,000-strong Arab Deterrent Force to intervene in the
Lebanese 1975-1990 civil war and made a major role in helping
achieve the reconciliation of warring factions. Now, Syria keeps
a special relationship with the country.
</P>
<P>
Late September, Lebanese Maronite Patriarch Cardinal Nasrallah
Butros Sfeir appealed Syrian troops to leave from Lebanon,
saying the current presence is against the establishment of
the country's independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
