<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Urges Closer Economic Ties with Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 26 (Xinhua) -- President Nursultan Nazarbayev of
Kazakhstan today called on Germany to boost its economic
activities in his country.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev, who is on a three-day visit to Germany, said during
a meeting with German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel today that the
potentials of the economic relations between the two country had
not been fully tapped.
</P>
<P>
Germany's investment in Kazakhstan still lagged behind that of
the United States, Turkey and South Korea, he told reporters today
in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev is scheduled to visit Frankfurt Thursday to seek
more investment from German companies in Kazakhstan's mining
sector.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Nazarbayev also met German President Roman Herzog
and Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Both German leaders stressed Germany's
willingness to strengthen the bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
German officials said Bonn would grant another 25 million marks
(14.4 million U.S. dollars) in development aid to Kazakhstan,
which would bring the total of its aid so far to 130 million marks
(74.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
During Nazarbayev's visit, the two countries also signed a
series of agreements on technological cooperation, double taxation
and education. Under one accord, Germany will send German teachers
to Kazakhstan, where about 350,000 ethnic Germans live currently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
