<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Confident of Better China-Canada Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CALGARY, Canada, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin, starting his state visit to Canada, today expressed
his belief that China-Canadian relations will surely be ushered
into the 21st century "with a brand-new outlook."
</P>
<P>
"My current visit to Canada is aimed at deepening
understanding, enhancing friendship, looking into the future and
developing cooperation," Jiang said upon his arrival at the
airport here today.
</P>
<P>
A 21-gun salute welcome ceremony was held at the airport and
red carpet rolled out for Jiang. The picturesque city of Calgary
is the first leg of his five-day trip, which will also take him to
Ottawa and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Canadian Governor-General Romeo LeBlanc Jiang
viewed the Guards of Honor.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement at the airport, Jiang also noted,"The
two sides should establish a trans-century China-Canada
relationship of all-round cooperation from the perspective of the
times."
</P>
<P>
"I am looking forward to having an extensive and in-depth
exchange of views with the Canadian leaders on the bilateral
relations and international as well as regional issues of common
interest," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jiang also indicated that he would take the
opportunity to make "extensive contacts" with the Canadians to get
"a first-hand knowledge of and draw on the development
achievements and experience of Canada."
</P>
<P>
"With joint efforts of both sides over the 27 years,
China-Canada relations have already been placed on a solid
foundation and are holding out a broad prospect for future
development," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president stressed the importance of a better
China-Canada relations.
</P>
<P>
"To further develop China-Canada relations on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit conforms to the fundamental interests
and common aspirations of the two countries and two peoples, but
also contributes to the peace and prosperity of the Asia-Pacific
region and the world at large," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang started his visit to Canada after taking part in the
fifth leaders' informal meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum in Vancouver on Tuesday.
The trip will also take him to Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
