<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Ready to Hold "Constructive Dialogues" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran today announced its
readiness to resume "constructive dialogues" with the European
Union (EU) countries following the end of the seven-month
standoff between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Republic of Iran is ready to embark on
constructive dialogues with all European states, provided that
they have the political resolve to correct their relations with
Iran and further adopt policies toward the Islamic Republic
based on mutual respect and free from outside influences," said
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi made the remarks in a response to the inclination of
European countries including Germany to re-open dialogue with
Iran, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The German daily Frankfurter Rundschau recently quoted a
German Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying that Bonn expected
the return of its ambassador to Tehran would be the preamble to
negotiations over all the issues of contention between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
All of the EU ambassadors returned to Tehran recently after
Iran and the EU reached an agreement over the diplomatic row
triggered by a Berlin court verdict accusing Tehran of sponsoring
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU countries recalled their ambassadors last April in a
protest to Iran after the Berlin court charged Iranian leadership
with involving in a case of political assassinations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
With the coming in office of the new government led by
President Mohammad Khatami, the EU countries insist on continuing
"critical dialogues" with Iran, though the United States has
intensified its sanctions on Iran by threatening to punish any
foreign company with over 20 million U.S. dollars investment in
Iran's oil and gas fields.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said British Minister of State for
Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs Derek Fatchett today also warned
the U.S. that its sanctions regime against Iran was damaging
its cooperation with the EU on a common policy toward Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Britain and its EU partners were opposed "in principle" to
the U.S. extraterritorial legislation and believed it was "better
not to isolate Iran totally," Fatchett said.
</P>
<P>
He told the Washington Institute for Near East Policy that
"sanctions against an EU company for making what are in my view
legitimate investments in Iran's hydrocarbon sector will lead to
a transatlantic row, which will benefit nobody but the hawks in
Iran."
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel reiterated earlier this
month that it was necessary for the EU states to resume
"critical dialogues" with Iran over the issues of international
terrorism, human rights abuses, mass destruction weapons as well
as Tehran's stance toward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
