<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Namibia Discuss Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The issue of illegal
immigrants flooding into South Africa from neighboring states was
raised by President Nelson Mandela in today's talks with his
Namibian counterpart, Sam Nujoma, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma is in Cape Town for a flying visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"One of the problems that concerns us, especially in South Africa,
is the large number of immigrants who are coming in, without full
compliance of the law," Mandela told reporters after the 90-minute
meeting with Nujoma at his official residence in Cape Town, Genadendal.
</P>
<P>
He said issues of bilateral and regional cooperation, particularly
trade and investment, had also been discussed.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said South Africa had an obligation to help its neighbors
to creat jobs and therefore curb illegal population flow.
</P>
<P>
It had become important to ensure that investment is spread over
the entire region, so that countries, where people can not earn a
living, are able to provide employment which can therefore prevent
people from moving across the border into other countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The problem is being addressed by the Southern African Development
Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
"But it is also fruitful to discuss this on a bilateral level to
ensure we assist SADC in search of a solution," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has a particular difficulty to deal with the issue of
illegal immigrants, because during the years of the anti-apartheid
struggle, liberation movements in South Africa had been given asylum
in neighboring countries, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we are victorious, they regard our victory as their
victory. They say now that our brothers and sisters are free in South
Africa, we can go there and look for jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, along with other SADC members such as Zimbabwe, is
critical of South Africa's economic dominance in the region and has
accused it of being too protectionist.
</P>
<P>
Namibia is also critical of South Africa's attempts to negotiate a
free trade agreement with the European Union, which it fears may be
detrimental to other SADC states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
