<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Welcomes EU Renewable Energy Blueprint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace today welcomed the
European Commission's formal adoption of the Renewable Energy
White Paper just five days before the opening of the United
Nations Climate Summit in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
"This is additional ammunition for the EU negotiators in
Kyoto," said Greenpeace EU advisor Aphrodite Mourelatou. "They are
now even better armed to argue that strong emission targets are
practicable and workable and must be adopted in Kyoto," she added.
</P>
<P>
The white paper calls for a doubling to 12 percent of the
contribution made by renewable energies by 2010 to EU energy
needs.
</P>
<P>
If implemented, this would deliver around one third of carbon
dioxide emission reduction needed to meet the EU's formal target
proposal of a 15 percent reduction in carbon dioxide and other
greenhouse gases by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace estimates that this could also create hundreds of
thousands of new jobs in wind and solar power within the EU and
generate a multi-billion dollar export industry.
</P>
<P>
"The Commission White Paper substantiates what we have known
all along -- that it is perfectly possible to replace
climate-destroying fossil fuels with clean renewable energy
technologies," said Karl Mallon, Greenpeace International Energy
Solutions campaigner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
