<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Boosts Agricultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
singled out agriculture and agro-allied productive base to form
part of the priority areas of government attention, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision is made because Nigeria basically has an
agrarian economy with "agriculture providing over 80 percent of
the nation's employment opprotunities and a respectable
proportion of the annual rate of growth of our GDP," said Ahlaji
Gidado Idris, Secretary to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
He said that this is part of the government resolution to
structure development efforts along the areas and sectors in
which the country has comparative advantage.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging that the country's foreign exchange
earning came largely from crude oil sales receipts, Idris said
that the inflow of petro dollars is a "dubious blessing to our
national economy as it never translated into enhanced and
proportionate percentage contribution to our gross domestic
product (GDP)".
</P>
<P>
He said, "Nigeria's population of nearly 100 million people
has to be fed, clothed, sheltered and found gainful employment in
agriculture until other sectors of our economy are sufficiently
developed to replace or complement crude oil and agriculture as
the mainstay of our economy."
</P>
<P>
A number of policies and programs have been initiated to
promote agricultural development in the country over the past 20
years. However, they failed to achieve their desired objectives.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the failure to political instability
and national disunity, the absence of national identity,
patriotism and commitment.
</P>
<P>
The present administration, which came to power in 1993 and
will quit next year, has been carrying out policies of guided
de-regulation and guided commercialization and privatization.
</P>
<P>
Veritable objectives and targets have been set for agriculture
and other sectors of the economy, Gidado Idris said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
