<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves Eurofighter Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament today gave
the greenlight to the controversial four-European-nation
Eurofighter project, clearing the last hurdle to production of a
21st-century warplane for Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget plan approved by the German parliament despite
strong opposition from the opposition parties, the German air
force Luftwaffe will be able to order 180 Eurofighter jets at
total costs of about 23 billion marks (13 billion U.S. dollars) in
the period between 2002 and 2014.
</P>
<P>
It will be the biggest and most expensive military project for
Germany in the post-war era.
</P>
<P>
The Eurofighter project have been controversial in Germany at a
time when Bonn is struggling with strict financial austerity to
meet the fiscal requirements for qualifying for the planned single
European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Development of Eurofighter prototypes has already cost German
taxpayers seven billion marks (four billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe, however, said that
Eurofighters are necessary to modernize the German air force's
out-of-date aircraft fleet which is dominated by Phantom jets.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz Aerospace AG, the German contractor of the
four-nation group that will build the modern jet, also argued that
the jobs and technological payoff of the project were
indispensable to the future of the company and a German place in a
European aircraft industry.
</P>
<P>
The other three European partners in the project, Britain,
Italy and Spain, have already approve the project, with London
planning to buy 232 Eurofighters, Rome 121 and Madrid 87.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the Eurofighter project is estimated at about
75 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
