<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Efficiency in Enforcing Judgements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today called for the rights
of EU citizens and businesses to be enforced through increased
efficiency in procedural law.
</P>
<P>
The commission made the proposal on the grounds that it
believes that it is both time- and cost-consuming to get a civil
or commercial judgement given in one member state recognized and
enforced in another.
</P>
<P>
It said that this kind of obstacle had obstructed access to
justice on equal terms across the EU market and that citizens and
small and medium-sized companies were the most vulnerable in this
respect.
</P>
<P>
Anita Gradin, EU commissioner responsible for justice and home
affairs, today held out the hope that "the measures proposed will
improve access to justice within the EU" and that this would
strengthen the rights of the citizen as a consumer as well as in
other roles.
</P>
<P>
A communication was adopted today by the commission in order to
contribute to the resolution of the problem, according to a press
release issued by the commission on the same day.
</P>
<P>
The communication also aimed at opening a wide debate on a
series of issues with a view to improving the possibilities of EU
citizens and businesses to enforce their rights through rapid
procedures for money claims and increased transparency of assets,
the commission said in the press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
