<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Adopts National Plan to Fight Greenhouse Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The French government today
adopted a national plan to fight global warming, or the greenhouse
effect, a few days before the opening of the world conference on
environment protection in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
When presenting the plan to the Council of Ministers, Minister
of Environment Dominique Voynet said that as economic growth
returns to France, the country should adopt at the same time an
ambitious plan to reduce the emission of gases which cause global
warming.
</P>
<P>
"If the growth returns to France, we should have an ambitious
program of action to reduce the greenhouse effect gas, that we
will realize with or without an agreement at Kyoto, because it is
beneficial," said Voynet.
</P>
<P>
Although the plan defines the priorities for environmental
protection without fixing statistics, it is the first in the world
and shows the will of France to fight against the greenhouse
effect, said observers.
</P>
<P>
The plan said that France is first of all favorable to the
policy of the European Union to impose taxes on energy products to
"harmonize fiscality" with a minimum tax rate on gas-oil products.
</P>
<P>
France will reinforce regulation on heating facilities of new
houses and establish a control system from 1999, while all
infrastructure of long duration, including houses, industrial
installations and transport infrastructure, must take into account
the greenhouse effect.
</P>
<P>
The government will support voluntary agreements with
industries which consume great amounts of energy, such as iron and
steel metallurgy, agricultural and food industry, paper and
cardboard industry, smelting, founding and casting industries, and
cement industry.
</P>
<P>
The minister praised the oil group Elf-Aquitaine for deciding
to reduce by 15 percent the emission of greenhouse effect gases by
2010, and encouraged small and medium-sized enterprises to
economize energy consumption.
</P>
<P>
The plan said that by the year 2010, transport will be
responsible for 40 percent of the emission of carbon dioxide,
therefore priorities will be given to the research on energy
consumptions, emission of polluting gases and motors of heavy
trucks.
</P>
<P>
The government will also elaborate laws on air cleanness in
cities, develop public transport such as collective transport and
railway and road transport.
</P>
<P>
In the long term, the European Union will reduce the emission
of carbon dioxide by vehicles from 165 grams per kilometer to 120
grams. The French automaker Renault will innovate its product to
reduce the emission to 140 grams of carbon dioxide per kilometer.
</P>
<P>
The government will also develop a program of economization for
electricity and heating generation centers, and to develop
renewable energy sources such as solar and wind energy.
</P>
<P>
The government will plan the planting of 30,000 hectares of
forests each year to increase wood resources for construction, and
will carry out information campaigns to raise people's awareness
about environment protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
