<HEADLINE> Russian Communist Leader Visits Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Communist Party leader
Gennady Zyuganov arrived here today for a three-day visit aimed at
promoting ties with the Iraqi ruling party and discussing efforts
to get the U.N. embargo on Iraq lifted or relaxed.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Baghdad, Zyuganov, also head of a large
party delegation, told reporters that he is glad to visit Iraq,
hoping that this visit will contribute to promoting ties between
Russian Communist Party and Iraq's ruling Baath Arab Socialist
Party, Iraqi News Agency (INA) said.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Zyuganov as saying that the Russian Communist
Party, the Duma (the lower house of the Russian parliament) and
the Russian people will continue seeking to get the seven-year-old
U.N. embargo on Iraq lifted, which bars Iraq from exporting its
oil.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Zyuganov comes after Iraq accepted a Russian
proposal last week to allow the United Nations arms inspectors
back to Iraq to continue their monitoring work of eliminating
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Baghdad expelled U.S. members of the inspection teams
in a crisis which threatened war.
</P>
<P>
Russia in return has promised to work for the lifting of the
crippling economic sanctions the U.N. Security Council imposed on
it after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
According to Iraqi parliamentary sources, Zyuganov will meet
Chairman of Iraq's National Assembly (parliament) Saadoun Hammadi,
and is also expected to meet a number of other Iraqi
officials. 
</P>
