<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministers to Meet on ASEAN Fund Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 27 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN finance ministers
will discuss the establishment of an ASEAN Fund, a standby credit
facility, at a meeting to be held here on December 1-2, a senior
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Fund would serve more as a confidence-building
measure given the adverse effects of recent currency attacks on
regional economies, Malaysian Treasury secretary-general Clifford
Herbert told a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he announced that a meeting of the finance ministers
of the Group of 15 (G-15) developing countries scheduled as part
of the December 1-2 meeting has been postponed to early next year,
as it would clash with a South American finance ministers'
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on the ASEAN Fund, Herbert said finance ministers
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) would decide
whether the fund would be independent of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
He said the quantum of the ASEAN Fund "has yet to be decided
..., but it will not be very large."
</P>
<P>
Herbert said the finance ministers would also discuss the
current economic situation faced by ASEAN member countries and
exchange views on the region's recent currency crisis and policy
responses needed to restore stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers from ASEAN members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam -- will be joined by their counterparts from China, South
Korea, Japan, the United States, Australia and Hong Kong, China,
he said.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus will join the ministers
to report on the progress of an IMF study on hedge funds and their
role in market dynamics, while the vice-president of the World
Bank would also brief the ministers on an initiative toward
strengthening the financial system in the region, the official
said.  
</P>
