<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges UNSCOM to End Inspections in 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 27 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) today called on the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
to close its files and end inspections in Iraq within six months,
the official Iraq News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
After an emergency session, chaired by Parliament Speaker
Saadoun Hammadi, the assembly said in a statement that the period
starts as of November 20 when UNSCOM resumed work in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had fulfilled all its commitments under U.N. resolutions,
said the statement while stressing the need for lifting the
sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly was convened to discuss Iraq's relationship with
UNSCOM, in charge of ridding Iraq of weapons of mass destruction,
and U.N. security council.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will take all practical measures in defense of its
legitimate rights, unity and national security, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi parliament also expressed high appreciation of the
Iraqi leadership's courageous and wise handling of "the historic
battle against American imperialism", said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Head of the assembly's Arab and International Committee Saad
Qassim Hamoudi slashed at the U.S. policy of trying to prolong the
embargo against Iraq and change its national leadership at the
session.
</P>
<P>
In order to bring an early end to the U.N. sanctions, the Iraqi
Revolution Command Council decided Wednesday to invite
representatives from the 20 countries that take part in the
U.N. inspection teams and experts or diplomats from the 15
U.N. Security Council members to inspect sites in Iraq under
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
These representatives can visit the presidential palaces "for a
period of one week or more, or for a month, so that they can find
out the truth," the council said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The invitations were made after U.N. weapons inspection teams
said the presidential palaces are the likely targets for hiding
weapons of mass destruction, like chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq could only be
lifted after U.N. inspectors verify that Iraq is disarmed of mass
destructive weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Make Contribution to ASEAN Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Treasurer Peter Costello told
parliament today that he expected Australia to make a major
contribution to next week's meeting of ASEAN finance ministers in
Malaysia's capital Kuala Lumpur, which aims to stabilize the
financial situation in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Costello made the remarks as he prepared to fly to Kuala Lumpur
to approve an early warning process to improve the international
community's response to further economic time-bombs in the Asian
region.
</P>
<P>
The December 1-2 meeting of ASEAN (Association of Southeast
Asian Nations) finance ministers and representatives from six
other nations including Australia, China and the United States is
expected to endorse what has become known as the Manila plan.
</P>
<P>
Costello said there would be a downturn in Southeast and North
Asia due to the region's recent currency and financial instability
which would in turn affect Australian exports.
</P>
<P>
"From the point of view of Australia, the downturn in the
Southeast or North Asian region affects Australia, it affects
Australian exports and it affects our jobs," Costello said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not only in the interests of the region but it's in the
interests of Australia to see financial stability return to the
region and economic growth strengthened."
</P>
<P>
Under the Manila plan, a new surveillance mechanism will ensure
that central banks within the region exchange information in a bid
to detect early signs of impending troubles.
</P>
<P>
The role of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) will be
strengthened, while arrangements will be developed to allow the
IMF to call on nations to supply supplementary funding for any
further rescue packages.
</P>
<P>
Australia has already committed 1 billion U.S. dollars to a
loan package for Thailand, offered another 1 billion dollars in a
second-tier of funding for Indonesia and is waiting for an IMF
request to assist in bailing out South Korea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
