<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest Conservatory Marks 70th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- China's oldest conservatory
today celebrated its 70th anniversary here in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Conservatory of Music, established in 1927 by
well-known educator Cai Yuanpei and musician Xiao Youmei, has
trained more than 5,000 music professionals.
</P>
<P>
From its beginning as a tiny school with 18 staff members and
23 students, the conservatory gradually developed into China's
music education center with more than 600 teachers and workers and
a regular enrollment of 1,000 students.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it can train its own doctoral and master's degree
candidates who specialize in music. Many students from the
conservatory such as Kong Xiangdong have become world famous.
</P>
<P>
During the last 20 years, its students have won more than 100
international music awards. From 1990 to 1992, four of its
students won international first prizes.
</P>
<P>
The conservatory also has trained 600 minority music workers
for 36 nationalities in China in the past 41 years.
</P>
<P>
Teachers and students also have composed music works which
combine Western style with Chinese tradition.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide alumni will organize 10 concerts to celebrate the
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
An international music symposium, to be attended by directors
of 24 conservatories worldwide, will also be held in Shanghai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
