<HEADLINE> World Bank Vows to Adjust to China's Changing Situation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will cater to
the changing situation and needs of China, maintaining annual
lending to the world's largest developing nation at around 2.5 to
three billion U.S. dollars, according to the bank's new chief in
China.
</P>
<P>
"We have developed and continued a very strong relationship and
we are now entering what we call a new stage," Yukon Huang,
director of the World Bank's China program, said in an interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The interview is the first Huang has granted in his capacity as
program director after his arrival in Beijing this month.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank's Strategic Compact and renewal process, which
is intended to transfer decision-making and responsibility to the
field offices and better utilize global knowledge and expertise,
will enable the largest international financial institution to
provide better, faster and cheaper services for its clients.
</P>
<P>
Drastic changes have taken place in China during the last two
decades as it advances toward a market-oriented economy, said
Huang, who is also chief of the bank's resident mission in China.
</P>
<P>
"There are lots of changes under way in China and the bank has
to adjust to the changing situation in China so that we will be
able to provide good service in the future," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
