<HEADLINE> Colossal Industrial Project Built in Coastal Province (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a modern
petrochemical center, the largest industrial project ever built in
Fujian Province, was unveiled at the Xiaocuo economic zone
recently.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost an estimated 100 billion yuan provided by
the Central Government in the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Xiaocuo will build a polyethylene plant turning
out 600,000 tons a year, a polyvinyl chloride (PVC) project with
an annual output of 300,000 tons, a 260,000-ton caustic soda
project and a 40,000-ton epoxy propane project.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the State Council has approved construction of a
refinery which is capable of refining 8 million tons of crude
oil annually at Xiaocuo. This will raise the annual oil refining
capacity of the Fujian Provincial Refining Company to 12 million
tons by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of this gigantic industrial project, Xiaocuo
will become a modernized harbor devoted to petrochemical
production on the western bank of the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Xiaocuo economic zone covers 319 square kilometers on the
southern bank of Meizhou Gulf with a population of 350,000.
</P>
<P>
The zone is 200 nautical miles from the port cities of Keelung
and Kaohsiung in Taiwan island and an hour's drive to Fuzhou, the
provincial capital, Xiamen Special Economic Zone and Jinjiang
city. The zone sits midway between Shanghai and Guangdong, two of
the largest industrial centers in the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The economic zone is also a deep-water harbor with a
5.5-kilometer coastline capable of accommodating 300,000-ton
ships. As a hub of communications, it has opened shipping routes
to all major harbors both in China and the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
