<HEADLINE> Philippine Opposition Names Senatorial Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' united
opposition, the Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino (LAMMP),
announced here today the first nine candidates in its 12-man
senatorial line-up for the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
However, the absence of Vice President Joseph Estrada and
Senator Orlando Mercado, chairman and president respectively of
the Partido ng Masang Pilipino (PMP), from the list fueled
speculation that the united opposition may be headed for a split.
</P>
<P>
PMP is one of the three members of the united opposition. The
other two members are the Nationalist People's Coalition (NPC) and
the Laban ng Demokratikong (Laban).
</P>
<P>
Reports earlier hinted at a brewing rift between Estrada and
Laban chairman Senator Edgardo Angara who are vying for LAMMP's
nomination to the 1998 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
PMP, NPC and Laban merged to form LAMMP but their leaders
continued to maintain their loyalty to their respective
presidential bets until the opposition's presidential
standard-bearer is formally named.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent move to display its unity, LAMMP issued a
statement saying the early announcement of its senatorial
candidates is one more proof that the united opposition will
remain intact until next year's elections regardless of whoever
will become the presidential candidate.  
</P>
