<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Vows to Adjust to China's Changing Situation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Huang explained that a strong relationship between the bank and
China, which rejoined in 1980, is built upon the fact that both
parties recognize the need to ensure that change will continue
during the process.
</P>
<P>
Huang said he will personally use the power he enjoys to ensure
that projects are performed better. The new World Bank official
was born in China's southwestern Sichuan Province and migrated to
the United States when he was five years old.
</P>
<P>
"One of my main responsibilities is to try as much as possible
to make sure that our program responds to the needs of the country
and the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Following the bank's internal reform package, directors of the
country programs now have much greater decision-making power than
their predecessors. In the case of Huang, he is empowered to make
80 percent of the relevant decisions concerning China projects.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that he has been impressed by the Chinese
government's commitment and desire to strengthen ties with the
bank, praising China as the best-performing country in
implementing bank-supported projects.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has always been serious about making the
best use of bank funds to ensure that the money is well-spent,
said Huang, who has been working for the bank since 1976.
</P>
<P>
"The government of China could be used in many ways as a model
of how governments work with the bank," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the new stage of bilateral relations between the
bank and China, both parties should view and seek to promote such
a relationship from the perspectives of change and development,
Huang said, hoping that the Chinese government will in the future
create better conditions for the implementation of bank-funded
projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Vows to Adjust to China's Changing Situation (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The bank is interested in supporting the Chinese government's
strategic plan to accelerate development in the more
under-developed central and western parts, but the fiscal strains
of local governments have made it hard to raise the matching funds
needed for bank loans, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, Huang strongly advises that the Chinese
government enforce an effective transfer payment system in the
central and western provinces and regions of China.
</P>
<P>
Huang, who was the bank's chief of business in Russia and six
central Asian nations prior to his current post, said that the
Chinese economy is very strong.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that to ensure long-term, healthy growth of
its national economy, China should improve its fiscal and pension
systems, reform its state-owned enterprises and commercialize its
state-owned banks.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the bank has approved 185
projects in China, with a cumulative loan portfolio of 28.2
billion U.S. dollars, including 9.1 billion U.S. dollars provided
by the International Development Association.
</P>
<P>
China has been the bank's single largest borrower for five
consecutive years since 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
