<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali People Mobilized to Help Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 27 (Xinhua) -- A large emergency
humanitarian meeting was held today at Ramadan hotel, north of
the Somali capital Mogadishu to discuss ways of helping flood
victims and coordinating donations from the local Somalis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by 70 members from local
non-governmental organizations (NGOs), the main communication and
airline companies, Muslim scholars, women groups, the Islamic
Solidarity Forum and the business committees from the two sides
of the bisected capital.
</P>
<P>
Mss Khadija Ossoble Ali, facilitator of the meeting, said
there are many wealthy Somalis who wish to donate food, money and
clothes, but don't know how. The meeting has formed a 11-member
committee from the participants to collect the donations so far
made by the business community and the well off personalities.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed on orienting and extending the
participation of the Somalis in the rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the establishment of an office for the 11
member committee was also agreed upon to carry out their
voluntary campaign in helping the needy people of the flood
stricken regions of southern and central Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Mss Khadija, representative of a local NGO, Adra Saacid, told
the press that the agenda of the meeting also include the effects
of the evacuated international NGOs from the capital.
</P>
<P>
"We can't fill the gap they left behind, but we should at
least give it a try," she said.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the meeting have issued an appeal calling
for the unconditional opening of Mogadishu's air and sea ports so
as to facilitate the on-going relief emergencies.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of the meeting criticized the
recent abduction of international aid workers and commended the
relief agencies for their enormous efforts in helping the flood
victims of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting called on all the Somali people in
and outside the country to sacrifice one day raw meal to
desperately needy people in the country.
</P>
<P>
This meeting came only two days after the international NGOs
evacuated their international staff from Mogadishu following the
brief abduction of two Italian aid workers Monday in Deganley
village, 25 km north of Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
