<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan's Judicial Crisis Intensifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has been plunged
into a grave constitutional crisis as the two sides of a split
Supreme Court have intensified their tug of war over the
appointment of Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah.
</P>
<P>
In a dramatic development of the ongoing judicial crisis, Chief
Justice Sajjad overturned an order for his own suspension
Wednesday night, which was issued earlier in the day by a
two-member bench of the apex court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court Quetta bench passed an interim order
Wednesday afternoon suspending Sajjad as Chief Justice while
hearing a constitutional petition.
</P>
<P>
The short order passed by the Quetta bench said that as a
result, Justice Sajjad shall cease to perform judicial and
administrative functions and powers of the Chief Justice of
Pakistan till further orders.
</P>
<P>
Reacting within hours of the passing of the interim order by
the Quetta bench, Sajjad issued a short order declaring that the
verdict of the Quetta bench had no legal effect for the reason
that proper procedure was not followed.
</P>
<P>
He said the bench had no authority to hear the petition
challenging his appointment. The two judges present at Quetta
bench had acted "without lawful authority," Sajjad claimed.
</P>
<P>
However, the dramatic intra-judicial row took a new twist
Wednesday night when the Quetta bench issued another order, saying
the earlier order by the bench concerning the suspension of the
Chief Justice "still holds the field and is hereby reiterated and
confirmed."
</P>
<P>
The Quetta bench challenged the appointment of Sajjad as the
Chief Justice on the ground that he was not the senior most judge
at the time of his promotion three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Sajjad to the top judicial post by the
president on June 5, 1994, "is held in abeyance," said the order
by the Quetta bench.
</P>
<P>
Under the Pakistani Constitution, only the senior most judge at
the Supreme Court should be appointed as the Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Sajjad has formed a five-judge bench
under him to hear two different petitions filed Wednesday
challenging the order of the Quetta bench holding in abeyance the
appointment of the Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ongoing tussle between the government and the
judiciary has also intensified as President Farooq Leghari refused
to accept the advice of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to appoint an
acting Chief Justice after the Quetta bench suspended Sajjad.
</P>
<P>
After the Quetta bench issued the interim order, Prime Minister
Sharif sent a summary to the president advising him to appoint
Ajmal Mian as the acting Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
However, President Leghari has sent back the summary without
signing it.
</P>
<P>
The developments at the Supreme Court have touched off a
constitutional debate in the country.
</P>
<P>
Some experts said that under the constitution the president is
bound to appoint an acting Chief Justice on the advice of the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Other experts, however, maintained that the president could not
make such an appointment in the light of the order of Chief
Justice Sajjad who had declared the order of the Quetta bench
invalid.
</P>
<P>
Now, the question remains of who is the Chief Justice of
Pakistan at the moment. While the government believes that Sajjad
stands suspended leaving the office of Chief Justice vacant,
Sajjad refuses to go.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the situation was further complicated late last
night when Justice Ajmal Mian, the senior most judge after Chief
Justice Sajjad, directed the Supreme Court office in the capital
to reconstitute the five-member bench hearing the contempt of
court case against Prime Minister Sharif.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0107 </DOCNO>
