<HEADLINE> PNG PM Urged to Resign over Bribery Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea(PNG)'s Prime
Minister Bill Skate was urged today by a major coalition partner
and the opposition to resign over corruption allegations.
</P>
<P>
The People's Progress Party (PPP), a major coalition partner,
said it would hold a special meeting at the weekend to advise its
caucus members on what action to take over allegations of bribery
against Skate, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Skate issued writs in the Queensland Supreme Court in Brisbane
today, suing the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) and
former government adviser Mujo Sefa for defamation over a
television report Wednesday night which alleged he authorized
1,300 U.S. dollars in bribes through his Internal Affairs Minister
Thomas Pelika, the AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Sefa, who secretly videotaped meetings between himself and
Skate and Pelika in his Port Moresby office last month, gave the
tapes to the ABC after a falling-out with other prime ministerial
staff.
</P>
<P>
In Brisbane, a spokesman for Skate said the prime minister was
distressed by the report and the adverse impact it would have on
PNG's reputation.
</P>
<P>
Skate, who was returning today from the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) leaders' meeting in Vancouver, Canada, has
strongly denied the allegations and labeled Sefa a blackmailer.
</P>
<P>
A group of opposition MPs led by opposition leader Bernard
Narakobi and former Prime Minister Michael Somare today also
called for Skate's resignation and an inquiry into the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
"We've called for his immediate resignation and we have also
called for Mujo Sefa to be extradited and brought into this
country and investigated by police," Narakobi said.
</P>
<P>
PNG former Prime Minister Rabbie Namaliu, who refused to join
Skate's coalition government formed in July, today also called for
an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The PNG Media Council also backed an inquiry after allegations
in the ABC report said that the money allegedly paid was to take
care of local journalists.
</P>
<P>
PPP leader Andrew Baing said the issue of corruption was of
paramount importance to the survival of democracy in PNG, but
added that he would not back calls for an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Another government coalition partner, the People's Democratic
Movement (PDM), stood behind party member Pelika and the ruling
coalition today.
</P>
<P>
"We are all together as a party and we are supporting the
current government," said PDM leader and Finance Minister Iairo
Lasaro at a joint press conference with Pelika.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Australian Prime Minister John Howard and Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer refused today to become embroiled in the
controversy, saying it was a matter for PNG to resolve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
