<HEADLINE> Changing Diets in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The dietary habits of
residents in Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, have
undergone noticeable changes.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey revealed that the city's per capita monthly
consumption of grains dropped from 12.4 kilograms in 1980 to 6.8
kilograms in 1996. Shanghainese eat an average 220 grams of rice
daily.
</P>
<P>
Pork consumed by the city's residents numbers 4.5 million
pigs and egg totals 58.8 million kg..
</P>
<P>
The city's residents formerly preferred traditional Chinese
foods such as soybean milk and deep-fried twisted dough sticks,
but now opt for beef, salads, cheese and various other Western
foods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
