<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Arms Experts Continue inspection in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Eight teams of the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) this morning continued
inspecting a number of suspected Iraqi weapons sites, the Iraqi
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The teams set out to monitor sites in and outside the capital
Baghdad this morning, and three helicopters would make aerial
surveillance, an Iraqi official who did not identify himself was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq is providing necessary facilities to the
arms experts to carry out their duties smoothly.
</P>
<P>
It is the sixth day in a row that UNSCOM experts go ahead with
their mission since their return to Iraq on November 21 after a
three-week break due to an Iraqi-U.N. standoff over arms
inspection.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday Iraqi President Saddam Hussein decided to invite
representatives of member countries of the U.N. Security Council
and UNSCOM to his palaces in order to make sure if he was hiding
weapons of mass destruction as alleged.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi decision fetched cautious welcome from weapons
inspectors and U.S. officials who have been threatening military
operations to force Baghdad into giving access to the palaces in
which they suspect biological weapons are stashed.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad had insisted that three presidential palaces were
"off-limits" to the arms inspectors because they were signs of
national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
This move is seen here as aimed at preempting U.S. arm-twisting
against Iraq and seeking a political means to have the crippling
U.N. sanctions, imposed after Baghdad sent troops to Kuwait in
1990, lifted as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. resolutions, UNSCOM must certify that Iraq has
eliminated its weapons of mass destruction before the Security
Council can remove the sanctions, including a ban on oil export.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish PM Visits NATO Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Polish Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek today visited the NATO headquarters to receive a letter of
invitation for accession from NATO Secretary General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
The visit was seen as the closing step of a two-month,
five-round accession talks between NATO and Poland.
</P>
<P>
The Polish prime minister told the press after his meeting with
Javier Solana that it was a very important day today and his
nation has been waiting for this day for "many many years."
</P>
<P>
"The (Polish) Solidarity Movement launched the accession move
17 years ago and the Poles have waited such a long time for their
wishes to come true, " said Buzek.
</P>
<P>
"Full-fledged membership is something the (NATO) secretary
general has promised us today," said Buzek who pledged that Poland
will assume the responsibilities required of a NATO member state.
</P>
<P>
Poland is expected to contribute 2.48 percent to NATO's common
budget which amounted to some 1.8 billion U.S. dollars in 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
Poland is now looking forward to the forthcoming ratification
process to be taken by the parliaments of the 16 NATO member
states early next year.
</P>
<P>
When asked if Poland should worry that possible Russian
counteraction will slow down the ratification process, the prime
minister said that diplomatic efforts will be made and major
attention will be paid to the good relations between Russia and
Poland.
</P>
<P>
Buzek said that his nation will try to resume quickly top-level
dialogue with Russia in terms of personal contacts and he was
hopeful that any problem pending will be solved on a top-level
basis.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that NATO-Poland ties and security in
Europe are the top considerations.
</P>
<P>
Solana said at a press briefing that it was through the
accession talks that the western military alliance came to know
how well Poland was prepared to join.
</P>
<P>
The protocol for accession is scheduled to be signed during the
December meetings of NATO defense ministers and foreign ministers
in Brussels while the formal accession is slated to take place in
April 1999 in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
