<HEADLINE> Merger Wave Hitting Steel Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- A merger wave is hitting the
Chinese iron and steel industry. One of the latest, and also the
largest, was the union of the Hubei-based Wuhan Steel and Iron
Company (WSIC) with two smaller local steel works -- Daye Steel
Plant and Echeng Iron and Steel Works.
</P>
<P>
On November 24 the heads of the three companies gathered in
Wuhan, capital of Hubei Province, and signed a merger agreement
amidst warm applause from officials of the Ministry of
Metallurgical Industry (MMI) and the local provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the three companies will form a new steel
group with WSIC as its flagship. The new group will have a
combined annual steel output of 8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Industry officials believe the merger will further consolidate
WSIC's position as the largest steel producer in central China and
is conducive to the development of all three parties.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this merger, Handan Iron and Steel Company (HISC), a
medium-sized steel producer in Hebei Province, took over Wuyang
Iron and Steel Company, a debt-ridden company in Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The event has generated much publicity because it was the
first major trans-regional merger case in the country's
metallurgical sector. The merger reportedly would not have
happened without support from the central government.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate the financial burden of HISC after taking over
WISC, the government has promised to arrange the listing of HISC
on the domestic stock market.
</P>
<P>
The biggest merger brewing in the Chinese steel industry is the
much-rumored union of Baoshan Iron and Steel Company (BISC) with a
number of iron and steel firms in Shanghai. The Baoshan merger is
said to have gained the support of MMI and the municipal
government of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations on the issue are under way," said Xie Qihua,
general manager of BISC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger Wave Hitting Steel Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If the Baoshan merger occurs, annual sales revenue of BISC
would reach 100 billion yuan, Xie said, adding that this would
enable the company to come a step closer to the goal of becoming
one of the world's top 500 enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qi, minister of MMI, said that the union will enable BISC
to become the country's largest steel producer which would be
capable of participating in international competition.
</P>
<P>
Other planned mergers include the union of the Anshan Iron and
Steel Company and the Benxi Iron and Steel Company, both located
in China's northeastern Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
As Anshan and Benxi, both among the top 10 steel producers in
China, are so closely located geographically, said Liu, there is
often a conflict of interest between them.
</P>
<P>
There long has been criticism of the irrational structure of
the Chinese iron and steel industry. A recent survey shows there
are more than 800 iron and steel producers in the country, of
which most are too small to have economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
The recently concluded 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China called for speeding up the establishment of
trans-regional, trans-industry and trans-national enterprise
groups with multiple ownerships in the state sector of the
country's economy to meet competition in the world economic arena.
</P>
<P>
"However, none of the 34 groups established in the country's
metallurgical fields in the past few years is up to standards set
for large groups," said MMI's minister Liu Qi.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that in the future many large steel
groups could be set up by merging existing iron and steel works
either according to their geographical proximity or according to
their business fields.
</P>
<P>
The country's total output of steel hit 100 million tons last
year, ranking first in the world. This year's volume is expected
to rise 6 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Observers in the industry said the recent mergers in the
Chinese iron and steel sector are just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
While encouraged by the trend, observers cautioned that the
establishment of such large groups should be established on a
voluntary basis and that excessive government intervention should
be avoided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
