<HEADLINE> Pakistan Chief Justice Suspended by Another Court Bench </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The on-going intra-judicial
row in Pakistan turned a new twist today as another division bench
of the country's Supreme Court suspended Chief Justice Sajjad Ali
Shah.
</P>
<P>
In its six-page short order, the Peshawar Bench of the court
endorsed an interim order issued by the Quetta Bench Wednesday
which barred the chief justice from performing his functions.
</P>
<P>
"In consequence, thereof, he has been restrained from passing
any judicial or administrative order in his capacity as Chief
Justice of Pakistan," the Peshawar Bench said.
</P>
<P>
The Quetta Bench Wednesday questioned the 1994 appointment of
Chief Justice Sajjad, saying he was not the most senior judge when
promoted by the government of former Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto.
</P>
<P>
Reacting within hours of the Quetta Bench's ruling, Sajjad
Wednesday night issued an order declaring the bench's verdict had
no legal effect because proper procedures were not followed.
</P>
<P>
However, the Quetta Bench issued another order late Wednesday
night, saying the earlier order by the bench concerning the
suspension of the chief justice "still holds the field."  
</P>
</TEXT>
