<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sexual Diseases, Drug Abuse Blamed For HIV/AIDS Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of AIDS (Acquired
Immune Deficiency Syndrome) cases is climbing in China because of
a "sharp increase" in sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) and
drug abuse, according to a medical report from a national AIDS
surveillance center.
</P>
<P>
"The infection rate of human immune deficiency virus (HIV)
which leads to AIDS, among sexually active people and drug abusers
has been rising over the past year," the report said, adding that
the situation could worsen if preventive measures are not taken.
</P>
<P>
The report was released by the center under the Chinese Academy
of Preventive Medicine, which established a national HIV/AIDS
surveillance network.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the network's report as saying that, out of 21
stations for monitoring patients visiting STD clinics across the
country, three stations found people infected by HIV in the first
six months of this year, compared with only one station in the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Out of 16 stations for monitoring prostitutes, four reported
women who tested HIV positive this year. None was reported last
year.
</P>
<P>
More than 187,800 STD cases were reported across the country in
the first half of this year, a rise of 12.5 percent over the same
period last year, the report quoted the National Center for STD
Control as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the AIDS epidemic is rising among drug addicts, not
only in southwestern China's Yunnan Province, but also in Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region and other parts of the country, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, most of the HIV infections in China are the result
of contaminated syringe needles used for taking drugs, 40 percent
to 60 percent of which usually are shared by drug users.
</P>
<P>
Out of 12 stations for monitoring drug addicts, seven found
people who were infected by HIV this year, compared with three
last year.
</P>
<P>
"China is facing a great risk of an AIDS epidemic because of
the rapid spread of STDs, since the majority of prostitutes in
China fail to take protective measures, such as using condoms,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Reported cases of HIV infection in China had reached 8,277 by
the end of last September, including 168 AIDS cases, according to
the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
"However, it is estimated that China has had at least 150,000
to 200,000 people infected by HIV," the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drug To Cut off Blood Supply to Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 27 (Xinhua) -- American scientists have found
that starving a tumor by cutting off blood supply to it has a
chance of working.
</P>
<P>
Tumors need blood vessels to provide them with nutrients and
growth factors which they use to grow unchecked. The idea of
starving them to death by targeting the blood vessels has been
around for 25 years. However, new and more powerful agents have
become available only recently.
</P>
<P>
Experiments show that the mice treated with Endostatin, an
inhibitor of new blood vessel formation, did not develop
resistance to the drug. Normally tumors respond to drugs by
developing resistance, and the more courses of treatment are
tried, the more resistant they become.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Boehm and colleagues from the Dana Farber Cancer Center
and Harvard Medical School, both in Boston, reported in the Nature
magazine that repeated use of Endostatin did not provoke
resistance in mice.
</P>
<P>
They were able to make lung cancers shrink even after six
successive cycles of treatment. In between treatments the cancers
were allowed to grow, then were treated again to test for
resistance.
</P>
<P>
None developed, and, most strikingly, all the treated
tumors became dormant even when treatment ceased. Why this
happened is not known.
</P>
<P>
Endostatin, the most powerful inhibitor of blood vessel growth
known, is a protein that has to be injected. It is expensive and
may have toxic long-term side-effects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
