<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Sets Up Fund to Promote IT Innovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore said today it has
set up a Multimedia and Information Technology (IT) Co-Investment
Fund of 50 million Singapore dollars (about 31.25 million U.S.
dollars) to beef up the country's efforts to become a center of IT
innovation.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the establishment of the fund at the National IT
Industry Summit, Minister for Education and Second Minister for
Defense Teo Chee Hean said the fund was to help build a vibrant
local industry for IT innovation and multimedia content
development in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be jointly managed by the National Computer Board
and the Singapore Federation of the Computer Industry (SFCI), he
said, adding that the fund will be used to co-invest in promising
start-up companies in multimedia and IT innovation which find it
difficult to raise capital to expand and grow.
</P>
<P>
By taking a stake in these start-up companies, which need not
necessarily be based in Singapore, the local industry can acquire
new technology and capabilities, and gain access to overseas
markets, Teo stressed.
</P>
<P>
Established mechanisms such as the IT Local Industry Upgrading
Program will be used to identify suitable candidates within the
SFCI member companies to enter into partnership with foreign
technology companies that can augment their capabilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Teo also said that in the next five years, the country will
focus on three areas to develop Singapore into the IT hub of the
Asia Pacific region: developing the Singapore people,
strengthening the country's connectivity with the world, and
establishing Singapore as a center for IT innovation.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's home ownership of computers has gone up steadily
and now stands at 41 percent of the households compared to 27
percent four years ago. In addition, 14 percent of the homes are
now connected to the Internet and the number of Internet dial-up
accounts in Singapore had increased from 17,000 in 1995 to 233,000
by the end of September this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
