<HEADLINE> UNITA Forces Mobilized in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Angola's general staff of the
armed forces disclosed here today that the country's former rebel
movement UNITA is mobilizing its militia forces and weapons in
certain areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Angola News Agency, the general staff said to
the local press that the military mobilization is taking place
mostly in Bie in the central part, Kuando-Kubango in the south
east, Uige in the north and Lunda-norte in the north east.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the operation started on October 29 when the
United Nations Security Council adopted a resolution to impose
sanctions on the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, some unidentified planes had invaded at
least 80 times Angola's territorial space, providing military
goods and equipment for the former rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, white mercenaries have concentrated in the area.
They not only offer military consultation to the UNITA forces,
but are also ready to launch attacks against the government army.
</P>
<P>
In Malange and Uige provinces in the north, soldiers belonging
to Mobutu Sese Seko, the late president of the former Zaire are
stationed on the UNITA's side, whereas in Cabinda province in the
north, forces loyal to Mobutu and former Congolese President
Lissouba also take the side with UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the general staff of Angolan army also indicated
the unstable situation in Cunene and Huila provinces in the south
of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
