<HEADLINE> China Records Good Harvest Despite Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- China achieved yet another
good harvest this year despite a severe drought north of the
Yangtze River, according to a leading official from the Ministry
of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
This summer's drought in north China, the worst since the
1970s, affected more than 33 million ha. of farmland and caused a
loss of 47 billion kilograms in grain output.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of Autumn has failed to relieve the drought
situation, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Autumn precipitation has been less than normal, with water
levels in north China's rivers falling by as much as 20
percent. One section in the lower reaches of the Yellow River has
remained dry for 222 successive days.
</P>
<P>
Water storage in the region's reservoirs has dropped by as much
as 33 percent, with water level in plains falling between 0.5 to
2.5 meters.
</P>
<P>
The recent rainfall in north China provided only slight
relief for the drought situation in Henan and Anhui provinces, as
well as in parts of Shaanxi, Shandong and Jiangsu provinces.
</P>
<P>
The drought has affected some 4.33 ha of winter wheat, and 1.6
million hectares of farmland remain fallow.
</P>
<P>
China has allocated over 9.44 billion yuan in the construction
of water conservancy projects. A record 75 million people have
worked to consolidate river dykes and reservoir and water
conservancy projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
