<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Overseas Hong Kong Emigrant Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today
said he hoped all Hong Kong emigrants living overseas would
contribute more to Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with 36 leaders of overseas Hong Kong communities
in the United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand, Li Peng
extended a warm welcome to them, saying he hoped more Hong Kong
emigrants would come to visit China's inland areas and would
undertake mutually beneficial economic cooperation and cultural
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to enhance understanding is to see with your own
eyes and tour yourselves," he said, adding he held the conviction
that through their tour this time they would see that China is
no longer what it was.
</P>
<P>
Especially in the past 20 years since the reform and
opening-up, he said, great changes have taken place, as China's
comprehensive strength has been greatly reinforced and the
people's living standard improved.
</P>
<P>
"The good momentum of China's stable political situation and
economic progress will continue," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
As all of the community leaders were emigrating out of Hong
Kong to the four countries, he said, they should be very concerned
about the Chinese government's policy toward Hong Kong and the
region's future development.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you all responsibly that the Chinese government
will adhere to its policy of `one country, two systems,' `Hong
Kong people governing Hong Kong' and a high degree of autonomy,
which it is now practising in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed: "We're full of confidence in Hong Kong's future
development."
</P>
<P>
He offered his wishes for success to the leaders in their
careers in countries where they live and that they would make more
efforts to improve relations between China and these countries.
</P>
<P>
Leaders present at today's meeting said that, although they
live overseas or hold foreign nationalities, they still cherish a
deep feeling for their native land and will always care about
China's modernization drive and the progress of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed their confidence in the development of the
inland areas and Hong Kong, adding that this was the first time
they organized an inland visit and that they believes more
emigrants will come.
</P>
<P>
They said that they are ready to contribute more to the
friendly relations between China and the countries they live in.
</P>
<P>
Guo Dongpo, director of the Office of the Overseas Chinese
Affairs under the State Council, attended today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show there are more than 1 million Hong Kong
emigrants living in the United States, Canada, Australia and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
These leaders represent more than 40 overseas Hong Kong
organizations, in which most of the members emigrated out of Hong
Kong in the 1970s and 1980s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
