<HEADLINE> Thanksgiving Turkeys Sell Well in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- As Thanksgiving day
approached, turkeys sold well at Beijing's large shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
In the supermarkets in the city's eastern section where many
foreigners live, a frozen turkey sold for 300 yuan. Roast turkeys
were even more expensive.
</P>
<P>
The Holiday Inn shopping center received more than a dozen
orders for turkeys today, and in the past week it sold more than
30 of the holiday fowl.
</P>
<P>
A clerk said turkeys were selling better than any previous
year. She said orders from businessmen and importers began as early
as August.
</P>
<P>
Of seasonal commodities on Beijing's market, orders for turkeys
are not significant, but they sell more easily. "The customers
are all foreigners," the clerk said.
</P>
<P>
A saleswoman at China Grand Hotel supermarket said that no
Chinese customers had bought a turkey in her store.
</P>
<P>
The main reason, she said, is that Thanksgiving Day is not
celebrated like Christmas, which is observed by some Chinese
people. She also said that her Chinese customers are not fond of
turkey meat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
