<HEADLINE> Engineer Assembly Opens In Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 engineers from
30 countries and regions gathered here today at a professional
assembly to exchange views on the future development of
engineering.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly of the World Federation of Engineering
Organization (WFEO) opened here today, the first time the Hong
Kong Institution of Engineers hosted the biennial meeting.
</P>
<P>
In her opening speech at the assembly, Anson Chan,
administrative secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), spoke highly of engineers' contributions to the
recent infrastructure development in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
She said: "One of Hong Kong's main attractions to business is
our well developed and maintained physical infrastructure ranging
from highways and telecommunications network to the drainage
system."
</P>
<P>
Engineers have done excellent work in the completion of many
infrastructure projects, such as the multi-billion dollar New
Airport Core Program, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled for operation next April, the New Airport and its nine
supporting projects, including land reclamation, highways,
bridges, a harbor crossing, and railways, will lay the foundation
for Hong Kong's continued prosperity in the 21st century, said
Chan.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1968 under the sponsorship of UNESCO, WFEO is a
non-governmental international organization with an aim to
encourage the application of technical knowledge to the economic
and social advancement of people around the world.
</P>
<P>
The federation is an assembly of national engineering
organizations from over 80 nations and regions representing 10
million engineers worldwide.  
</P>
