<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG PM to Sue ABC over Bribery Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG) Prime
Minister Bill Skate will sue the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC) and former government adviser Mujo Sefa for a
television report on Wednesday evening which alleged he authorized
payment of bribes.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's spokesman Chris Branwell told the
Australian Associated Press that defamation writs would be issued
in the Supreme Court in Brisbane today.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for Skate sought an injunction in Brisbane late
Wednesday to try to stop the ABC report from going on the air but
failed because it was lodged too late, Branwell said.
</P>
<P>
He said further revelations would be made after Skate was
briefed by his lawyers when he returned from the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) leaders' informal meeting in
Vancouver, Canada.
</P>
<P>
"We will issue other statements after the PM has had time to
have discussions with legal representatives in Brisbane," Branwell
said from Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Skate is very distressed over the matter. Not only for
himself, but also for the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ABC report was based on secret video tapes made by Sefa in
his Port Moresby office.
</P>
<P>
One of the videos shows Sefa and Skate discussing payment of
1,300 U.S. dollars to Internal Affairs Minister Thomas Pelika.
</P>
<P>
A meeting taped later shows Sefa telling Pelika that the prime
minister had authorized the payment.
</P>
<P>
Pelika is filmed accepting an envelope from Sefa.
</P>
<P>
Both Skate and Pelika have denied the bribery allegations and
labeled Sefa a blackmailer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
