<HEADLINE> Building Infrastructure For Future Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition "Build for the
 Future" opened here today, highlighting Hong Kong's major
infrastructure projects being undertaken to meet new challenges
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, organized by the Works Bureau and other
government departments, is aimed at promoting Hong Kong's
expertise and professional services in infrastructure development,
said a spokesman for the Works Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Photographs, models and multi-media equipment were used to
present the latest achievements Hong Kong has made in the field.
</P>
<P>
Visitors to the exhibition first caught a glimpse of the ten
Airport Core Program (ACP) projects now heading into the final
line. Scheduled to go into operation in April, 1998, the Chek Lap
Kok New Airport and other supporting projects -- land
reclamation, a crossing harbor, highways, bridges, and railways --
 will provide for Hong Kong the solid infrastructure foundation
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
The estimated cost of the ACP projects hit 155.3 billion HK
dollars (20 billion US dollars), a massive investment that is
expected to yield substantial returns in overall economic benefits
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the ACP projects, the exhibition also illustrated
the development of new towns, land formation, major road links,
and sewage disposal schemes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
