<HEADLINE> Hainan Uses World Bank Loans for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, an island province in
south China, has used World Bank loans to develop an education
program.
</P>
<P>
Being the first such project to use World Bank loans, the
overall program, which was funded with a loan of five million
U.S. dollars from the World Bank and domestic funds of 3.98
million yuan, focuses on introducing compulsory education to eight
poverty-stricken counties, including Tuncang, Qiongzhong, Tongzha,
Lingshui and Baoting counties.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official said the program will ensure the eight
counties can help meet the targets for nine-year compulsory
education set by the State Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
The funds will also be used to improve conditions at several
normal schools in Hainan Province, including the Hainan Normal
School of Nationalities, the Hainan Normal School of Foreign
Languages and the Hainan Oriental Normal School. 
</P>
