<HEADLINE> Malaysian Investors Invited to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia today invited
Malaysian businessmen to exploit its vast natural resources and
develop business linkages in the high technology sector.
</P>
<P>
"We want to open our big market to Malaysian businessmen who
will have a good future to expand their business," Russia-ASEAN
Cooperation Fund (RACF) Chairman and Director-General Vladimir
Saoutov said here today.
</P>
<P>
Saoutov, who is in Malaysia on a week-long market survey
mission, told a news conference that RACF was prepared to help
Malaysian companies to make a quick entry into the Russian market
by providing consultancy services in legislation, logistics,
licensing, visa and legal services.
</P>
<P>
He said he was in Malaysia to promote trade and economic
cooperation between the two countries and seek business
opportunities which could be taken by either Malaysian or Russian
companies.
</P>
<P>
Russia is well-known for its rich raw materials, hi-tech
industries and defense especially in the field of aerospace, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Saoutov said the Malaysian private sector could venture into
businesses ranging from machine building, electronics, consumer
goods, food processing, textile, furniture industries and exchange
of expertise in defense technology.
</P>
<P>
"We are creating a favorable climate for expanding the presence
of private companies from ASEAN countries following our
government's decision to support private business enterprises," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Russian private sector was willing to cooperate
with ASEAN especially after Russia's admission as a member of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between Malaysia and Russia stood at 400
million U.S. dollars last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
