<HEADLINE> Spink's Auction in HK Reaps 2.7 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The two-day auction of rare
coins and stamps by the Spink, a dealer in fine arts, has yielded
almost 21 million HK dollars (2.7 million U.S. dollars), proving
that the Hong Kong market is "still strong."
</P>
<P>
At the Spink's coin and banknote auction on Tuesday, 77 percent
of the lots were sold by value, which was described by Spink
Director Mark Rasmussen as "a great achievement" under the
circumstances of the recent currency and stock market turbulence.
</P>
<P>
The top lot of that day's auction was a rare Queen Victoria
Hong Kong Silver Pattern One Tael, sold to an Asian buyer at
667,000 HK dollars (86,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Among the banknotes, the top lot obtained 414,000 HK dollars
(53,000 U.S. dollars), more than double its estimated price. This
5-dollar Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation note was
issued on January 1, 1867, the first date of issue for this type,
making it an extremely important banknote in the Hong Kong
currency series.
</P>
<P>
At the stamps and covers auction on Wednesday, a
double-surcharged Chinese Red Revenue stamp issued in 1897
garnered 552,000 HK dollars (71,000 U.S. dollars) while three
precious Hong Kong stamps were sold for over 100,000 HK dollars
(13,000 U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Neill Granger, specialist for the Spink's Stamp Department,
commented: "The Hong Kong market is still very strong but is
selective, with top quality and rare items in strong demand from
international buyers."
</P>
<P>
The Spink, an old art dealer based in London, stages auctions
annually in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
