<HEADLINE> International Meeting on Gender Studies Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- An International Conference
on Gender and Development in Asia opened here today at the Chinese
University of Hong Kong to examine the role of women in the fast
growing economies in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Fanny Cheung, chairperson of the Equal Opportunities Commission
of Hong Kong, addressed the opening ceremony of the three-day
conference, the first major one of its kind in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Social changes and economic development in Asia are affecting
the roles and lives of women. "While there are increased
opportunities, barriers remain and gender disparity is still
common," Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, as in many other parts of Asia, promoting equal
opportunities and eliminating discrimination are still at a very
early stage, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The Equal Opportunities Commission is a relatively new
organization in Hong Kong. The commission and the Sex
Discrimination Ordinance went into full operation about one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Four distinguished scholars, including Professors Tani Barlow
of University of Washington, Esther Chow of American University,
Elisabeth Croll of University of London, and Maria Mies from
Germany are invited as keynote speakers.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are some 100 people from Hong Kong,
China's inland areas, Taiwan, Malaysia, India, Singapore and some
North American and European countries. More than 50 papers
focusing on three major themes -- gender and political
development, gender and social change, and gender, sex and
violence -- will be presented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
