<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Exit From IMF by Yearend: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
reiterated that the Philippines will exit from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) by the end of this year, a news release from
the Presidential Palace said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told the Financial Times of London during an interview in
New York that there are only two pieces of legislation to be
approved by Congress for the Philippines to be ready to say
"goodbye" to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
These are the Comprehensive Tax Reform Program and the
Agricultural Modernization Law.
</P>
<P>
These two programs, which are the preconditions for the country
to exit from the IMF's 35-year tutelage, are now being harmonized
by the bicameral Conference Committee and are expected to be
passed soon.
</P>
<P>
Ramos is in New York for an overnight visit after attending the
5th leaders' meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Ramos said the Philippines will likely
surpass its export projection this year because the country had
already achieved 25 billion U.S. dollars during the first nine
months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the projection of the gross national product
(GNP) growth has been lowered by one percentage point following
the financial turmoil in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The revised target is from 5.5 to 6.5 percent for 1997. Last
year, the GNP grew by 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also said that foreign investments continue to come in
despite the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"We targeted 500 billion pesos (14.5 billion US dollars) for
1997 (but in) the first nine months, we had already achieved 613
billion pesos (17.8 billion dollars) of registered investments in
our Board of Investments," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
