<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Large Business Groups Begin Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korean business groups
have begun belt-tightening restructuring efforts to adapt to
expected changes in the business environment following the
introduction of International Monetary Fund (IMF) loans.
</P>
<P>
The Samsung Group, one of the nation's best-performing
conglomerates, Wednesday announced a set of retrenchment measures
aimed at coping with the economic crisis and bolstering its
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
It would shed 30 percent of its organization, dispose 34
business lines involving 2,000 employees, reduce 30 percent of its
original investment, reduce the executives' salaries by 10
percent, freeze the wages of the entire staff, and shorten
decision-making processes.
</P>
<P>
The group would also intensify efforts to restructure its
business portfolio. Some marginal businesses would be abolished,
with others to be handed over to small-sized firms and resources
generated from this process would be channeled into promising
"seed" business lines inside the group.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Hanwha Group also disclosed a
restructuring plan highlighted by a 10 percent reduction in
investment, the lay-off of executives and staff, the sell off or
collaboration of three companies and a scale down of its 400
billion-won (about 0.364 billion U.S. dollars) building complex
plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other business groups, including Hyundai, LG and
Daewoo, were also reexamining their investment plans for next year.
</P>
<P>
As a desperate way out, Halla Engineering &AMP; Heavy Industries
Ltd., one of the core companies of the 12th largest Halla Group,
announced on Tuesday to halve its 6,000-strong workforce to 3,000,
withdraw from unprofitable businesses, sell off real estate and
reduce the wages of its remaining workers and executives, thereby
preparing for a possible deterioration in cash flow.
</P>
<P>
Business experts predicted that Halla's decision to lay off
about 3,000 workers, the single largest announcement ever by a
South Korean company, would have a ripple effect on other
cash-strapped companies, which fear liquidity crunch in the wake
of the IMF's restructuring process.
</P>
<P>
They were worrying that as much as 20 percent of the 890,000
employees working in the top-ten large conglomerates may lose
their jobs during the restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
