<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Slightly on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined
slightly on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index lost 2.58 points to close at 1650.97 today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the banking stocks were among those chalking up
the biggest price gains on institutional buying.
</P>
<P>
The unstable financial markets in other parts of the region
have driven institutional investors to allocate their funds to
Singapore, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 203.25 million units,
valued at 340.4 million Singapore dollars (about 212.75 million
U.S. dollars). Advances overtook declines by 232 to 116 while 270
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Local computer maker IPC Corporation was the most actively
traded stock as it registered a turnover of 35.64 million units.
It was followed by Singapore Telecom which had 7.903 million
shares traded. Rekapac was next with 7.3 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
The DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign led the gainers
of the day as it rose by 70 cents to finish at 14.7 Singapore
dollars. UOB (United Overseas Bank) Foreign increased by 65 cents
to end at 9.6 Singapore dollars while the SPH (Singapore Press
Holdings) Foreign gained 50 cents to close at 22.1 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, IPCO was the biggest loser as it declined by
38 cents to end at 2.8 U.S. dollars. Asean Fund fell by 30 cents
to close at 8.7 U.S. dollars and Bukit Sembawang and the SPH lost
20 cents each to finish at 11.9 and 15.6 Singapore dollars
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
