<HEADLINE> Zambia to Strengthen Campaign Against Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will strengthen its
campaign against child labor, which is on the increase in the
country due to a vicious cycle including poverty and diseases,
Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted a report of the Parliamentary
Committee on Women, Youth and Child Development as saying that
many children engaged in child labor are orphans of AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Zambia is one of the countries hardest
hit by the HIV/AIDS epidemic and it is estimated that between
80,000 and 100,000 people will die of AIDS this year alone.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Labor and Social Security Minister Syacheye Madyenkuku
told parliament Wednesday that the ministry will now direct more
of its efforts toward the scourge of child labor with a view to
eliminating it.
</P>
<P>
He called on the public to provide information on those
employing or encouraging child labor so that they could be
brought to book.
</P>
<P>
MP Nakatindi Wina from the ruling party said child labor in
the country is rampant and seems to be on the increase mainly as
a result of poverty.
</P>
<P>
She deplored the unavailability of statistics on child labor
at both the Ministry of Sport, Youth and Child Development and
that of labor and social security.
</P>
<P>
Independent MP Austin Chewe said Zambia has attained economic
growth through private sector initiative which needs to be backed
by supporting the children.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Select Committee criticized the ever
increasing number of child vendors that have flooded the
country's streets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
