<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Set up Pilot Task Forces to Combat Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will establish two pilot
interdiction task forces in the provinces of Nghe An and Lai Chau
respectively to help law enforcement agencies combat drug
trafficking, the country's police chief said here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the police, the customs and border guards in
the two provinces will join hand in assisting law enforcement
agencies in fighting drug trafficking, general director of the
People's Police Truong Huu Quoc told a two-day workshop on
cooperation among anti-drug law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, 15,176 drug cases involving 24,453
people were reported in Vietnam, with a seizure of 170 kilograms
of heroin, 7,108 kilograms of opium, 10,718 kilograms of
marijuana, and millions of narcotic ampoules and pills, according
to figures released at the workshop, which started today.
</P>
<P>
50 percent of the drugs were seized along the Lao border in Lai
Chau province, and the opium seized in Nghe An province in 1997
alone made up half of the total opium confiscated in the country,
the police chief said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organized by the Ministry of Interior and the
United Nations Drug Control Program.
</P>
<P>
At present, the plantation area of opium poppy has shrunk to
1,400 hectares in Vietnam, but drug trafficking was still on the
rise, he said.
</P>
<P>
A great amount of opium and heroin sold in the country was
trafficked from neighboring countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
