<HEADLINE> OAU to Enhance Women's Role in Africa: Salim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim,
Secretary General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
said the OAU is exerting maximum efforts to enhance women's role
and contribution in peace building efforts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing session of the three-day workshop on
documented best practices of women in peace building and
non-violent means of conflict resolution here Wednesday, Salim
noted that over the previous years OAU has been giving much
attention to the promotion of the role of African women in
socio-economic and political endeavors in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, OAU has been working toward the establishment of
the African women's committee for peace called for in the 1993
Kampala action plan on women and peace.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee is intended to serve as a framework to
facilitate the participation of women in institutions and
mechanisms created by the OAU for conflict prevention, management
and resolution as well as in all other policy organs and sectoral
fora of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA)
and OAU.
</P>
<P>
''Women are equitably represented in the executive body of the
secretariat,'' Salim pointed out, adding that one of the guiding
principles of the OAU is to give priority to female candidates
among candidates of equal competence and experience.
</P>
<P>
He urged OAU member states to include women in their
delegations at the various meeting of the secretariat so as to
ensure that women are given appropriate consideration with the
OAU policy organs at all levels.
</P>
<P>
Women activities drawn from Burundi, Congo Brazzaville,
Liberia, Mali, Rwanda, Sudan, Somali and Ethiopia as well as
representatives of government and inter-government organizations
and U.N. agencies attended the three-day workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
