<HEADLINE> Mandela Reiterates Need for Single Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today reiterated his view that South Africa need a
single capital city.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after receiving the Freedom of the City of Cape Town
at a ceremony in the city hall, Mandela said he was confident
the Captonians would help the country grapple with this complex
but urgent question.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was referring to the argument about relocation of the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest survey, the majority of urban South
Africans want parliament to stay in Cape Town rather than to be
moved to Pretoria, the administrative capital of the country.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has three capital cities: Pretoria (executive),
Cape Town (legislative) and Bloemfontein (judicial).
</P>
<P>
Lots of time and money were wasted as government officials and
parliament members have to shuttle between the capital cities.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has been studying the possibility
of relocating the national legislature to save the government
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
However, relocating parliament is no easy job. According to
independent assessment, moving parliament from Cape Town to
Pretoria could cost 3.5 billion Rand or 745 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
