<HEADLINE> Seminar Marks 25th Anniversary of China-New Zealand Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Fruitful political, economic
and security cooperation between China and New Zealand is not only
in the fundamental interests of the two peoples, but will also
promote prosperity and stability in the Asia-Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
Officials, experts and scholars attending today's seminar
marking the 25 anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties
between China and New Zealand reached a consensus that the two
nations have complementary economies and vast potential for
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the development of cooperation in all
fields, including economic and trade areas, will facilitate the
further advancement of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have enjoyed smooth cooperation since forging
diplomatic relations in 1972. Statistics through the end of
September show that the bilateral trade soared to 453 million US
dollars, up from 9.7 million US dollars in 1972. China is
currently New Zealand's fifth largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
China's investments in New Zealand have increased dramatically
over the past few years, with the majority of funds going to the
forestry sector. New Zealand is one of China's primary targets for
overseas investment, with contractual investments from the former
flowing into the latter standing at 277 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Teng Teng, vice president of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, noted that China, the largest developing country in the
Asia-Pacific Region, has enjoyed sustained political stability
and economic growth accompanied by social stability.
</P>
<P>
He added that China's vast potential market will enable New
Zealand to expand economic and trade contacts in the Asia-Pacific
Region.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand, a developed country, has abundant experience in
development, utilizing and processing farm and primary products,
and advanced technology, said Teng. He said China can learn a
great deal from New Zealand in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Paul Clark, director of China Studies and the University of
Auckland, and Bryce Harland, New Zealand's first Ambassador to
China and current director of the New Zealand Institute of
International Affairs, also addressed the seminar.
</P>
<P>
The University of Auckland and the Institute of Asia-Pacific
Studies under the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences are jointly
sponsoring the two-day seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
