<HEADLINE> Indian PM Hopeful of Solution to Political Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral said today that he was hopeful of a solution to the
political impasse arising from the Congress party demand for
removal of three ministers from the United Front government, the
Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers belong to the Dravida Munnetra Kazagham
(DMK), a regional party in Tamil Nadu which was indicted for being
linked with the 1991 assassination of former prime minister Rajiv
Gandhi by a judicial inquiry report.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party has pressed for their ouster from the Gujral
government, warning that it will otherwise withdraw its crucial
support to the minority government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after holding a brief meeting with
Congress party President Sitaram Kesri in the parliament house
here today, Gujral said: "I am always hopeful of a solution."
</P>
<P>
But he evaded questions as to whether he would send a formal
reply to Kesri's second letter handed over to him last night
reiterating the party's demand to sack the DMK ministers.
</P>
<P>
Gujral on Monday had rejected a similar Congress demand
conveyed by Kesri in his first letter to the prime minister last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with Gujral, Kesri evaded all
questions but remarked: "one thing I have to say, that is, I am
totally opposed to the dissolution of the Lok Sabha (the lower
house of Indian parliament)."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a top Congress party leader said today that if the
United Front failed to meet the demand to sack DMK ministers, the
Congress party would have no option but to withdraw support and
stake its claim to form government.
</P>
<P>
The United Front government led by Gujral needs support from
the Congress party to ensure a majority in the Lok Sabha.
</P>
</TEXT>
