<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Beef up Affirmative Action by Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- South African employers
could be fined up to 900,000 Rand or 187,000 U.S. Dollars for
failing to implement affirmative action, under the Employment
Equity Bill unveiled in Pretoria Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to local media today, the bill provides for
employers having more than 50 employees to take active steps to
ensure that employees at the company reflect the racial
composition of the South African population.
</P>
<P>
Three quarters of the population are blacks and about 14
percent are whites.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, companies would be required to draw up a plan
according to which it planned to remove inequalities in this
composition and submit this plan to the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
The plan had to specify what measures would be taken to
identify and eliminate employment barriers, including unfair
discrimination which adversely affected blacks, measures to train
blacks, a policy of affirmative action and measures to
accommodate blacks.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides for a fine of 500,000 Rand or 104,000
Dollars to companies refusing for the first time to comply with
the act, up to a maximum of 900,000 Rand for a company which has
four previous convictions for contravening it.
</P>
<P>
A Commission for Employment Equity would be appointed with a
chairman, who is to be named by the labor minister, with the duty
of advising the minister and doing general research on equality.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department will listen to comments on the bill until
February next year and then it hopes to push it through
parliament by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
The system of apartheid had left South Africa with a legacy of
inequality and workplace discrimination was still a fact, local
media reported.
</P>
<P>
The wealthiest 10 percent of households, mostly white, capture
50 percent of national income while only 1.5 percent of the
national income was distributed to the poorest 20 percent of
South Africa's population. Blacks occupied the lower grades of
employment with whites occupying 96 percent of top positions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
