attended the celebrations and said Vietsovpetro would serve as the
mainstay for Russian-Vietnamese economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin left Vietnam Wednesday evening, ending his
three-day official visit, the first one by a Russian prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations were also attended by officials from Vietnam's
leading oil industry body Petrovietnam and the Russian external
economic relations organisation Zarubejneft.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's President Tran Duc Luong, General Secretary of the
Communist Party of Vietnam Do Muoi and National Assembly Chairman
Nong Duc Manh sent seperate messages of congratulations to the
celebrations. 
