<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Back From APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China, returned here today after attending the Fifth Informal
Leaders' Meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the airport, Tung told reporters that the
meeting, held in Vancouver on November 24 and 25, was of
particular significance to Hong Kong as this was the first time
for Hong Kong to participate in the meeting under the name of
"Hong Kong, China" under the policy of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
He said President Jiang Zemin, who also attended the meeting,
reaffirmed to him the importance of the policy of "one country,
two systems" and expressed his concern over Hong Kong's measures
to deal with the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, leaders of the 18 APEC members exchanged
views on the situation in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders were optimistic about the long-term development of
the economy in the Asia-Pacific region despite the fact that some
economies were affected by the recent financial turmoil, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed that the Asia-Pacific region will still be an
important region in the 21st century which can match North America
and Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders discussed the financial volatility in the region
and agreed that the best way is to deal with it under the
leadership of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
"I have taken this opportunity to brief other leaders of APEC
members on Hong Kong's economic development, the SAR government's
determination to maintain the linked exchange rate and why we have
confidence in this policy," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also discussed the liberalization and facilitation
of trade and investment and the deepening of economic and
technological cooperation in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Vancouver, Tung also met with overseas Hong
Kong people and informed them of the present situation and future
development of Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
