<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Confident of Early Recovery of Asian Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today expressed confidence that the Philippine stock market
and other stock markets across Asia will recover from the effects
of the currency crisis soon.
</P>
<P>
With the commitments of the world's leading economies to assist
the most distressed economies in Asia under the International
Monetary Fund framework, stock markets in the region are bound to
recover, Ramos said at a video conference with members of his
Cabinet in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Ramos is on a working visit to New York now.
</P>
<P>
He said that based on the assessment of the APEC leaders, the
"basic qualities of Asia-Pacific economies remain strong and
solid, these most affected economies are bound to bounce back."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a news release from the Presidential Palace quoted
Ramos as saying that apprehensions over an "Asian meltdown" as a
result of the ongoing currency turmoil were "grossly exaggerated."
</P>
<P>
"Without a doubt, the problems are no mere passing headache for
Asian economies. But I believe, to paraphrase Mark Twin, that all
the talk of an Asian meltdown is grossly exaggerated," Ramos told
300 business leaders and financial analysts in New York.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said Asian leaders consider the current financial crisis
as more of a wake-up call than a turning-point on the road to high
growth.
</P>
<P>
Since the economic fundamentals of most countries in East Asia
are still strong, it would be obviously premature to write East
Asia off from the investors' business calculations, Ramos pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
To substantiate his view that East Asia remains conducive to
investments, Ramos said the World Bank has just forecast an
average Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth rate of 7.6 percent
for the region over the period of 1997 to 2006.  
</P>
</TEXT>
