<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Audit Senior Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
ordered the audit of senior civil servants in all ministries,
parastatals and agencies.
</P>
<P>
A list of such staff should be compiled and forwarded to the
presidency not later than December 12, says a government
circular.
</P>
<P>
The essence of the audit is to "aid communication within
federal government establishments" as the circular demands an
up-to-date record of each ministry or agency for inclusion in the
1997 Federal Office Directory.
</P>
<P>
The submissions should include designations, names, office
telephones and addresses of those to be audited, it says.
</P>
<P>
But some senior civil servants are apprehensive of the motive
of the exercise, the national newspaper This Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody is sure of his job any longer. Not after names of
those to be sacked before an upward review of salaries can be
effected," a senior official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The fresh order followed a similar government directive at the
instruction of the head of state General Sani Abacha for the
rationalization of federal workers as a precondition for salary
increase.
</P>
<P>
The rationalization is needed because the government believes
the existence of a big number of "ghost workers" in government
departments.
</P>
<P>
The impending cut in the number of civil servants after the
rationalization has aroused anxiety among government staff at low
levels.
</P>
<P>
The audit, according to the newspaper, would also enable the
government to know the various officers manning strategic
positions in government with a view to encouraging
professionalism in the service.
</P>
<P>
The circular ends with a threat that ministries and agencies
which do not return the submissions will not only be listed, but
will also face sanctions.
</P>
<P>
But it does not specify what kind of sanctions would be faced.
</P>
<P>
It is noted that this is another major move of the Abacha
administration in its effort to streamline the government over
the recent two weeks.
</P>
<P>
On Monday last week, Abacha ordered immediate dissolution of
the 36-member cabinet. Only three ministers remain in their
posts. The new cabinet is expected to be establish soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
