<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Percent Growth Expected for Lebanon's GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's gross domestic
product (GDP) is expected to grow by 4 percent in real terms in
both 1997 and 1998, a report of HSBC James Capel said today.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's nominal GDP in 1998 is estimated to rise to 17.20
billion dollars from 15.15 billion dollars expected for 1997,
according to the report issued by the leading brokerage house of
the country.
</P>
<P>
It predicted per capita GDP in 1998 will reach 5,228 dollars
from 4,749 dollars this year and that the inflation rate will ease
to 8 percent from the current 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the James Capel report cited the country's trade
deficit, growing domestic debt and high budget deficit as the
major concerns.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has witnessed a negative trade balance since the end of
the civil war in 1990 due to surging demand for imports of
construction materials.
</P>
<P>
But the report hailed a cut of trade deficit to 49.5
percent of the GDP in 1996 from 65 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Lebanon's foreign debt will arrive at
3.05 billion dollars by the end of 1997, or 20 percent of the GDP,
which the report said is not so serious a problem as the domestic
debt.
</P>
<P>
"Net domestic debt is expected to reach 10.8 billion dollars by
the end of 1997, or 71.3 percent of the GDP," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said unemployment in 1996 was around 18 percent, and
productive sectors, mainly industry and agriculture, contributed
less than 25 percent to the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Activity on the Beirut Stock Exchange could be boosted by new
listings over the next months and estimated the over-the-counter
market at 25 percent of the official market in value.
</P>
<P>
It expected that Lebanese companies will continue raising funds
on international market meet the needs of expansion. Six Lebanese
banks and financial institutions have collected a total of 1.085
billion dollars on the markets since mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's current account deficit fell to 36.1 percent of the
GDP in 1996 from a record high of 65.9 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lebanese Central Bank said that Lebanon has an
overall positive balance of payment amounting to 743 million
dollars in 1996 despite the high current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a recent report that Lebanon has 6.08 billion
dollars of foreign exchange reserves by the first half of November
compared with 5.885 billion dollars at the end of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
