<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokesman on Act Passed by Australian Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- China sincerely hopes the
Australian government will adopt effective measures to prevent
events which might in any way harm Sino-Australian relations,
according to Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the remarks during this afternoon's regularly
scheduled press conference in response to a question concerning an
act recently passed by the Australian Senate. The act demands that
the Australian government appoint a "special coordinator for
Tibetan Affairs."
</P>
<P>
"We strongly resent the fact that the Australian Senate passed
an act designed to interfere in China's internal affairs," said
Tang, adding that China firmly opposes any move to create a
so-called "special coordinator for Tibetan Affairs."
</P>
<P>
The fact that Tibet is an inseparable part of China has been
readily acknowledged by the international community, said Tang. He
emphasized that no foreign country should or has the right to
interfere in the Tibetan affairs which are purely internal affairs
of China.
</P>
<P>
The act passed by the Australian Senate runs counter to the
good momentum in the development of Sino-Australian relations,
according to Tang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
