<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French National Assembly began to debate Wednesday a draft
law presented by the Minister of Justice Elisabeth Guigou, which
expects to allow the naturalization of children born in France of
foreign parents at the age of 13, if they have lived in France for
five years. Since 1993, children born of foreign parents in France
can no longer obtain French nationality unless they require it
between the age of 16 and 21.
</P>
<P>
-- One in 100 adults in 15-49 age group in the world is infected
with HIV, the virus which causes AIDS, and only one in 10 persons
infected with HIV is aware of his/her HIV status, said a new United
Nations World AIDS Day report published on Wednesday, which warns
that the HIV epidemic is far worse than previously thought. Updated
surveillance techniques uncover 16,000 new infections a day, while
30 million people now live with HIV/AIDS, according to the report
published by Professor Peter Piot, general director of UNAIDS
program.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French government is ready to present the first draft law
on the reduction of work week to 35 hours from 39 hours by the year
2002 for all salary-earners. For enterprises with more than 20
workers, the reduction of working week will start from January 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
-- The AIDS epidemic continues its ravage in the world with only
the industrialized world having controlled the expansion of the
disease, said the annual report by the UNAIDS program on Wenesday.
Ninety percent of the HIV/AIDS patients live in developing
countries. In Africa, 8 percent of people of 15-49 age group are
carrying HIV virus. India is the country most touched by AIDS with
three to five millions HIV/AIDS virus carriers. The epidemic risks
to expand considerably in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
