<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Reduce Govt Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
decided to reduce 59,000 employees by the end of 1999 in
accordance with its revised public service reform program (PSRP),
the state-owned Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The first 7,000 employees are to be laid off by the end of
December 1997 while another 8,000 jobs will be phased out by
April 1998, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Peter Machungwa, labor and social security minister,
as saying in parliament Wednesday that the government has worked
out two separate package schemes under which employees will be
laid off and compensated for the loss of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
There is a voluntary separation package scheme to be given to
permanent and pensionable civil servants while the second option
will be a compulsory separation package scheme for classified
workers.
</P>
<P>
Among other measures the government has put in place to
facilitate the PRSP include an immediate staff recruitment
freeze, payroll clean-up, reviewing and terminating recent
appointments of all non-professional workers aged 55 years and
above.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa said, the government will not continue awarding
salary increases to a "bloated" public service because it takes
away resources from productive sectors to personal benefits.
</P>
<P>
The considerable reduction of staff, together with large-scale
privatization of state-owned and parastatal industries, will
certainly deteriorate the poor country's employment situation and
keep high the unemployment rate, which is estimated
conservatively at about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The PSRP was launched four years ago by President Frederick
Chiluba in an effort to reduce the redundant staff and government
expenditures in salary and promote efficiency in public services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
