Ramos, who is currently on a visit to New York, made the
announcement in an interview with the Financial Times of London, a
news release from the Presidential Palace said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I will announce within 10 days the person I will endorse for
the presidency, including the entire ticket of Lakas, or as soon
as we get home," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos will fly back to Manila on December 2.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos said he has not made up his mind yet on who to
endorse for the presidency because the selection process is still
going on.
</P>
<P>
The formal endorsement of the administration party's
presidential bet will be made during the party convention in
January 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are eight Lakas presidential aspirants seeking the
endorsement of the president, but Lakas spokesman Alberto Lumauig
said the choice has been narrowed down between Speaker Jose de
Venecia and former defense secretary Renato de Villa.
</P>
<P>
The other six are Chairman Manuel Morato of the Philippine
Charity Sweepstake Office, Senator Ramon Magsaysay, Senator
Heherson Alvarez, Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo, Bulacan
Governor Roberto Pagdanganan and Economic Planning Secretary
Cielito Habito.
</P>
<P>
Despite reports that the choice will be between De Venecia and
De Villa, Ramos is not saying anything, keeping everyone,
including his close aides, groping in the dark.
</P>
<P>
The Lakas-NUCD conducted consultation caucus earlier this month
and gave the president a blanket authority to pick the standard
bearer of the party.
</P>
<P>
The presidential elections will be held on May 11, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ramos can no longer run for reelection since he is barred by
the 1987 Constitution. A move to amend the charter was abandoned
amid nationwide protests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
