<HEADLINE> Australian Stock Market Closes Slightly Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- A sharply stronger Tokyo
share market and a sturdy performance by Australia's
telecommunications giant Telstra helped offset further falls in
gold stocks today, winching the local bourse off its early lows to
finish slightly down.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 0.8 points softer at 2462.3,
after at one stage dipping 18.1 points to 2444.2.
</P>
<P>
Losses across the gold index outpaced yesterday's 21.7 point
fall. The sector shed 39.6 points or 4.4 percent today to end at
861.1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, gold was trading in Sydney 1.70 US dollars lower at
296 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The gold index obviously took a battering," Reynolds &AMP; Co's
Grant Williams said.
</P>
<P>
"But Telstra was very strong and that probably helped give a
bit of confidence to other stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index slipped 8.3 points to a close of 1051.8
and the industrials sector climbed 7.3 to 4229.7.
</P>
<P>
Australia's leading resource company BHP moved up 9.1 cents to
13.30 Australian dollars, and global miner Rio Tinto ended 13
cents weaker at 16.17 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
News Corp gained eight to 7.77 Australian dollars and its
preferred stock ended seven cents stronger at 7.09 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telstra led the top turnover by volume table, with 70.39
million installment receipts changing hands worth 130.6 million US
dollars. The receipts gained eight cents to 2.77 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia's most profitable bank, NAB, lost five cents to end
at 19.30 Australian dollars, CBA bank dipped four cents to 17.51
Australian dollars, ANZ bank climbed seven cents to 10.00
Australian dollars and Westpac bank moved up six cents to 9.21
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 391.61 million shares, valued at
880.6 million US dollars. Falls outnumbered rises, 636 to 518,
with 441 steady.  
</P>
