<HEADLINE> Kenya Moves to Reduce Farmers' Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
taken measures to reduce grain farmers' losses as the torrential
rains pounding the country have hampered maize and wheat
harvesting, according to a Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
W.K. Koitaba, managing director of the National Cereals and
Produce Board, was quoted as saying that grain farmers in the
country had incurred heavy crop losses and unexpected drying
charges because of the heavy rains in the past one month.
</P>
<P>
To reduce their losses, he announced, the board has reduced by
half its drying and cleaning charges "during this critical and
unfavorable weather period".
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official noted that the board had also raised the
moisture limit to 18 percent for maize delivered to depots with
dryers while depots without drying facilities would continue to
accept maize with a moisture level of up to 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, central, northeastern and western regions of the
east African country continued receiving high rainfall amounts
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kenya's Meteorological Department yesterday
indicated that Nairobi received the highest rainfall, more than
21 millimeters, followed by the northeastern area of the country
which received about 20 millimeters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Tariffs Benefit China's Balanced Growth of Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- China's constant and extensive
lowering of tariffs will promote a balanced growth of China's
imports and exports, and will not initiate a situation in which
imports influence its macro-economy, experts say.
</P>
<P>
China has reduced import tariffs five times since 1992. The
average tariff level was reduced from last year's 23
percent to 17 percent on October 1, 1997. Earlier this week,
Chinese President Jiang Zemin pledged that China will lower the
average level to 10 percent by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the measure is to help increase imports and lower
the trade surplus so as to create a better balance in China's
foreign trade, according to Professor Li Yushi from the
International Trade Research Institute under the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China's exports have grown much faster than imports over the
past two years. Exports climbed by 26 percent by the end of June
this year compared with the same period of 1996, while imports
remain at last year's level. The nation's trade surplus
reached 17.8 billion US dollars for the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
To obtain a rapid economic development, China needs the
importation of more advanced technology and equipment, as well as
resources in short supply, said Li, adding that China hopes the
tariff cuts will reduce import costs and promote the growth of
imports.
</P>
<P>
Li Jian, deputy director of China's Foreign Trade Office, said
that the establishment of foreign-funded enterprises in China will
enable Chinese businesses to import advanced equipment, quality
raw materials and spare parts needed to upgrade product quality
and enhance market competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
He added that the international community will welcome
practical measures China has adopted to further open its market,
and noted that related efforts will promote the nation's
entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Li Yushi agreed with Li Jian, saying that the measure will
create a better environment for China's entry into the WTO. He
added that the increase of imports will alleviate
trade frictions between China and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Li Yushi said it is unnecessary for state-owned enterprises to
worry about the pressure from the increase of imports, and noted
that imports currently hold only a small share of the
Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that state-owned enterprises should
strive to adapt themselves to the highly competitive international
market. He also noted the worldwide trend toward free trade and
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Li Jian said China's domestic market has, in fact, established
extensive, direct ties with the outside world. Those industries
and departments which opened earlier have not as yet been
saturated with imports. On the contrary, the quality of their
products has been improved and some of them have been exported.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
