<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Aquatics Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The east China coastal province
of Fujian has established an export-oriented aquatics industry,
and has emerged as the world's largest eel processing center.
</P>
<P>
An official from the provincial aquatics department said the
sector's goal is to establish large-scale specialized production.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Fujian's 20,000 ha. of aquatic breeding bases
produced 100,000 tons of aquatic products in 1996, with the 2,000
ha. specialized eel production base recording exports of over
60,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Processed eel products from Fujian hold 40 percent of the
international market, with annual exports earnings from roast eels
standing at 450 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's 480 foreign-funded joint ventures specializing in
aquatics production involve investments of over 360 million
U.S. dollars, according to 1996 figures. Enterprises funded with
investments from Taiwan account for 50 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics for the first half of 1997 show that the
province used foreign investments of over 100 million
U.S. dollars, a figure equalling the total for the previous two
years.
</P>
<P>
The official said the province is also applying for World Bank
loans of 70 million U.S. dollars to promote the sustainable
development of marine resources.
</P>
<P>
The official noted provincial plans through the end of the
century call for establishing the sector as a pillar industry with
an annual output of 4.9 million tons and earnings of 39.5 billion
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
