<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Pays Tribute to Former Malawian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has described the death of former Malawian
President Kamuzu Banda as regrettable.
</P>
<P>
Although Banda did not have a very good reputation for
retaining links with apartheid South Africa, he had "done some
remarkable things" for liberation movements in Africa, Mandela
said in Cape Town Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Banda funded the Patriotic Front in Zimbabwe and ensured other
liberation armies had the necessary weapons to conduct their
struggle, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Banda led Malawi to independence in 1964 and ruled the country
for 30 years until he was ousted in the first democratic
elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Banda, who underwent brain surgery in South Africa in 1993,
was hospitalized in Malawi on November 15, suffering from fever
and pneumonia. He was rushed to Johannesburg for emergency
treatment two days later.
</P>
<P>
He died of respiratory failure in a Johannesburg hospital on
Tuesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
