<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comatose Patient Revived </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in Nanjing, east
China's Jiangsu Province, have revived a comatose patient
following 30 days of electrotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The course of therapy marks the first time Chinese doctors have
successfully used electrotherapy to revive a comatose patient.
</P>
<P>
Several months ago, Zhu Lixing, 36, lapsed into a coma
resulting from an intracerebral hematoma. Zhu remained in a
comatose state following removal of the hematoma, according to
today's Guangming Daily.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the China Brain Revivification Center, affiliated
with the Nanjing Marine Medical School, conducted high-level
consultations and decided to treat Zhu by using electrotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The first procedure involved inserting a 3-cm electrode in the
patient's cervical spine. Doctors then administered one hour
courses of electrotherapy six times a day.
</P>
<P>
An electroencephalogram (EEG) conducted on the second day of
treatment indicated the patient was breathing on his own, with
doctors detecting simple movements on the third day.
</P>
<P>
The center continues to use high-pressure oxygen therapy along
with electrotherapy. Zhu has regained normal functions related to
speech and movement of the upper limbs.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that the patient has completely recovered from a
comatose state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
