<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Becomes Dominant User of Port Mombasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Ports Authority
(KPA) has named Tanzania the third biggest user of the port of
Mombasa among the transit countries, the East African Standard
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a statement issued by the KPA managing
director Lenny Mwangola as saying that Tanzanian traffic passing
through the port of Mombasa increased to a record 345,670 tons
last year from 91,358 tons in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that "this contradicts certain press
reports that the sole Kenyan port is losing business to its
neighbors."
</P>
<P>
Transit traffic handled at the port totalled 1.7 million tons
in 1994, 1.9 million tons in 1995 and 2.8 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the transit countries, Uganda has recorded a steady
performance in the last three years with 915,000 tons in 1994,
1.1 million tons in 1995 and 1.2 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is the biggest user of the Mombasa port while the
second largest transit user is Rwanda whose traffic amounted to
780,831 tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that the KPA attaches great
importance to the Uganda market and those of the other Great
Lakes region countries and that was why the port opened a liaison
office in Kampala recently to assist shippers.
</P>
<P>
The port handled total traffic of 8.3 million tons in 1994,
8.0 million tons in 1995 and a record 8.6 million tons last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
