<HEADLINE> COMESA Court of Justice to Be Established in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) is to set up a court of justice in
Zambia in a bid to meet requirements for interpretation of the
grouping's treaty, Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the COMESA Council of Ministers has
approved a 229,000 U.S. Dollars budget for the court which will
be manned by a permanent registrar and seven high court judges
who will work on part-time basis.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Alfeyo Hambayi, commerce minister and chairman of
the council, as describing the creation of the court of justice
as "a landmark" decision by his council.
</P>
<P>
The court will, among other things, provide interpretation on
the provision of the COMESA treaty signed in 1994 and ensure that
member states comply with the COMESA time table of program
implementation, said Hambayi at a news briefing Wednesday here.
</P>
<P>
Erastus Mwencha, acting COMESA secretary general, said at the
last weekend the court comes into being in line with the
development of the increasingly active grouping.
</P>
<P>
There are already many pending requests for the interpretation
of the treaty provisions which requires the involvement of an
autonomous body such as the court, said Mwencha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
