<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Housing Reform in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The south China city of
Guangzhou has initially established a socialized and
commercialized housing system compatible with the nation's market
economic system.
</P>
<P>
Vice-mayor Shen Bainian said the new housing system is
characterized by the establishment and perfection of public
fund-raising and housing allocation systems.
</P>
<P>
Shen said the two systems have strengthened the role the State,
collectives and individuals play in raising funds for housing
construction.
</P>
<P>
The housing funds accumulation system introduced to more than
6,800 units by the end of April this year involved one million
workers and staff, with total funds surpassing 1.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The funds accumulation system has also played an important role
in promoting housing construction. Loans of 820 million yuan from
the public fund were used for housing construction by the end of
1996, greatly easing housing shortages for over 20,000 families.
</P>
<P>
The city has sold nearly 260,000 state-owned apartments to
residents since the introduction of housing reform, with over
three billion yuan returned to the fund during the first stage.
</P>
<P>
The city has also raised rental fees in line with market
demand. Rental costs will account for an average 15 percent of
household income by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
