<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Relics Moved out of Downtown Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Some Late Stone Age relics
that were discovered at a construction site in downtown Beijing
have been moved so that work on an overseas-funded project won't
be disrupted.
</P>
<P>
A number of stoneware items and animal fossils dating back
20,000 years were discovered at the Oriental Plaza's construction
site on Wangfujing Street, at the end of last year. Archaeologists
say that they are the oldest ever found in the central part of the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
When the relics were discovered, construction work was
suspended, and archaeologists have visited the site repeatedly
since March, according to Wang Wuyu, deputy-director of the
Beijing Cultural Relics Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
In order to keep the site intact but not stop the construction
work, archaeologists decided to move the earth containing ancient
traces and store it in a museum in Beijing for the time being. So,
they cut a 200-sq.m. olace into 3- to 4-sq.m. pieces around the
relices, and covered them with special paper to keep their
original shape, and put them in special wooden boxes to move
them. The work took nearly 20 days.
</P>
<P>
"After an exhibition center is built on the site in the
Oriental Plaza, the earth of the ancient site will be replaced,"
Wang explained.
</P>
<P>
Li Cunxin, of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences' Institute
of Archaeology, said that exhibits of pottery, stone implements,
bronzes, and other archaeological findings are not uncommon for a
museum, but it's rather difficult to put an entire historical site
in a museum.
</P>
<P>
"We can only display photos of the sites and written
descriptions, meaning a big restriction on researchers," Li
noted. But, after the ancient site is restored, Beijing will have
another Stone Age site in addition to Peking Man at Zhoukoudian,
southwest of the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convict Tells Court of Plan to Kill Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 27 (Xinhua) -- A jailed convict has described
how he waited for the "right time" to detonate a Claymore mine
that would blow off Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe's entire
motorcade near the National Sports Stadium in Harare.
</P>
<P>
William Namakonya, a Malawian, was giving evidence Wednesday
before High Court Judge Justice Chatikobo on the third day of the
treason trial of opposition ZANU Ndonga leader Ndabaningi
Sithole.
</P>
<P>
"I was waiting for 2 p.m. because that is when the motorcade
was going to pass," Namakonya said, adding, "the right time did
not come because I was arrested before it was time."
</P>
<P>
Asked how he had established the motorcade's time, Namakonya
said together with his accomplice Philemon Feranando, an
ex-Mozambican soldier, they had studied that 2 p.m. was the time
that Mugabe passed the stadium on his way to his rural home in
Zvimba.
</P>
<P>
He is serving 12 years after he pleaded guilty to possession
of arms of war linked to the assassination bid on Mugabe on
August 18, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Namakonya and Feranando worked for Sithole as security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Namakonya testified that Sithole was involved in the plans to
kill Mugabe as he had sanctioned the collection of the two
Claymore mines, an AK assault rifle and ammunition from
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement to kill Mugabe was with Sithole starting from
the time we were told by Sithole to go to Chipinge of Mozambique
to collect the mines," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sithole has pleaded not guilty to recruiting people for
military training in Mozambique between 1983 and 1995 in order to
overthrow Mugabe's government.
</P>
<P>
The veteran nationalist has also denied conspiring to kill
Mugabe and possessing arms of war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
