<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mindanao Infrastructure Development Accelerates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The construction of vital
infrastructure facilities in Mindanao, the southern Philippines,
has been intensified during the last five years, as a result of
focused support from the national government.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by various government agencies showed that
as of this year, more than 2,200 kilometers of roads in Mindanao
have been paved, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 34 percent of these roads or a total of 773
kilometers were paved by the national government in just five
years.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao's power generating capacity increased by 44 percent or
501 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The early completion of two major ports in the cities of Davao
and General Santos also reflects the administration's seriousness
in facilitating the development in Mindanao, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A number of airports in Mindanao were further improved and two
major airport projects in Southern Mindanao were accomplished by
the administration.
</P>
<P>
An international airport in General Santos has been completed
and is currently operational, while the Davao International
Airport was also upgraded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the administration is eyeing for the construction of
the first two lines of the Mindanao railway which will connect the
cities of Davao, Cotabato, Iligan, and Cagayan de Oro.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure budget for Mindanao for 1998 will be
increased to 7.01 billion pesos (203 million US dollars), which is
almost double from the 3.6 billion peso (104 million dollar)
budget for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao has economically lagged behind the other regions in
the country due to its backward infrastructure facilities and an
unstable law and order situation.
</P>
<P>
The Ramos administration has made great efforts in recent years
to push the development in Mindanao, especially after it forged a
peace accord with a main Muslim separatist Moro National
Liberation Front last year, which ended nearly 30 years of war in
the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
