<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River To Get Two New Bridges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Two new bridges are being
built across the Yellow River in Lanzhou, the capital of northwest
China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongli Bridge, named for the Zhongli Group, a Gansu
enterprise that has spent more than 10 million yuan on it, will be
a 310-m. suspension bridge, with a main tower 37 m. high. It will
be finished by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Yintan Super Bridge, financed by the Lanzhou Economic and
Technological Development Zone at a cost of 160 million yuan, will
be 803 m. long and 25 m. wide in the central section. It will be a
cable-stayed bridge that can withstand earthquakes registering 8
on the Richter Scale, and will be finished in May of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Yellow River, China's second longest, divides Lanzhou into two
parts. The first bridge across the river, connecting the northern
and southern parts of the city, which is still in use, was built
of iron in 1907 and reinforced in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The two new bridges, which were designed by the Ministry of
Railways' No.1 Survey and Design Institute's Bridges and Tunnels
Division, will make conditions better for developing the northern
part of Lanzhou City and will relieve the traffic problem in the
city proper, local officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
