<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq's Offer Should be Judged by UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Reacting to Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein's invitation of U.N. experts and diplomats to his
palaces for weapons checking, the United States said Wednesday
that it is up to the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) to judge the
sincerity of the offer.
</P>
<P>
"UNSCOM has a job to do. That is to locate and destroy weapons
of mass destruction in Iraq. Any Iraqi offer needs to be judged by
UNSCOM against this standard," State Department spokesman James
Foley said.
</P>
<P>
Foley said UNSCOM "must be allowed 'immediate, unconditional
and unrestricted access to any and all areas' it wishes to
inspect."
</P>
<P>
The INA, Iraq's news agency, said Saddam's invitation "is in
response to the lies and falsifications of American officials."
</P>
<P>
The United States has demanded Iraq let U.N. weapons inspectors
enter 78 sensitive areas, which were said to be Saddam's
residential palaces and Villas, alleging that there might be
hiding weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq first rejected the demand, calling it an encroachment of
"national sovereignty." But on Wednesday, Iraq decided to invite
two representatives of countries that are involved in the
inspection of its weapons and five experts or diplomats from
countries in the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. State Department official said the offer seems to
be a significant breach in the Iraqi line.
</P>
<P>
"It could be a welcome step if it means real access, if it
means that UNSCOM inspectors will go into the sites and be able to
do their work in all of these sites unhindered. And that's
obviously the question that we can't answer today," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
