<HEADLINE> India to Launch Two Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- India is to storm into the
commercial satellite-launching market next year when its
indigenously-built Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle (PSLV-C2) puts
two remote sensing satellites into space, the local press said
today.
</P>
<P>
One satellite will be from South Korea and the other will be an
Indian remote sensing satellite, IRS-P4.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium held in Andhra Pradesh on Wednesday, D.
P. Rao, director of India's National Remote Sensing Agency, said
that by the turn of the century, India could have the largest
number of remote sensing satellites with wider range and better
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The IRS-P4 will be followed by IRS-P5 which will have a sharper
eye that can beam back pictures with 2.5 meters resolution, he
added. 
</P>
