<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to End Tests on Food Import From SAARC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
planning to stop radiation tests on food imported from other
countries of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC), Commerce Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed import policy for 1997-2000 has prescribed a total
withdrawal of radiation tests on food items imported from India,
Pakistan, the Maldives, Nepal, Bhutan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new import policy would ensure that the items are
produced in the countries exempted from the radiation test.
</P>
<P>
However, local businessmen and commerce officials fear that
unscrupulous traders might use the new policy to get radiated food
items into the country.
</P>
<P>
As a result, huge quantities of rice, wheat, corn, fruits and
vegetables might pour into the country unchecked, local press
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Among SAARC members, India tops the list of food exporters to
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission scientists will continue to
check the radiation level in all food items imported from
countries other than SAARC members, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
