<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Dairy Industry Showing Some Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The dairy industry of China
is suffering from product surpluses but has enormous potential,
people attending an international symposium held here by the
Shanghai Milk Group were told recently.
</P>
<P>
A company source told Xinhua that, since 1993, the country's
dairy industry has grown 6 to 10 percent annually, and in 1996,
produced 6.25 million tons of dairy products. That figure is
expected to reach 7.8 million tons by the year 2000 and 17 million
tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
However, dairy products still account for a very small part of
the country's food industry, which had an industrial output value
of 600 billion yuan in 1996, while the dairy sector merely
accounted for 0.4 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita milk consumption in China is now 5 kg a year,
compared with 300 kg in developed countries, 36 kg in
developing nations, and the world average of 105 kg.
</P>
<P>
Many domestic producers face a problem of serious
over-stocking, and a large number of dairy farms are losing
money. Global milk producers compete in the Chinese market, while
local state-owned milk makers are losing their market-share.
General Administration of Customs statistics show that China imported
298,000 tons of dairy products from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
New products like fresh milk and yoghurt do well and have an
increasingly larger share of the local market, and small milk
producers have formed a number of large groups, and some private
companies are getting involved in the business.
</P>
<P>
The two companies, Inner Mongolia Yili and Beijing Sanyuan,
have become the first milk producers to be listed on the stock
market, and several other companies are planning for issuing
shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
