<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeastern Chinese Province Pushing Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province, a major heavy industrial base, is using its private
sector to invigorate its economy, which has been dominated by
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is planning Liaoning's first
provincial-level meeting of private entrepreneurs as the starting
point of its strategy to encourage the private sector, according
to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Governor Wen Shizhen recently told a group of government
officials that the provincial government hopes to remove all
ideological obstacles in the way of private economic
development. The private sector should have its own political
status and a sound ideological and social environment must be
created for it.
</P>
<P>
Merely trying to reinvigorate large and medium-sized
state-owned firms is no answer, he said, and there is no
contradiction between developing the private sector and reviving
the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has decided to abolish or revise
local policies and regulations that block the way of developing
the private sector, while more preferential policies are being
considered, and private enterprises are being encouraged to get
involved in hi-tech industries, processing, and consumer goods,
the governor said.
</P>
<P>
For a long time now, Liaoning has been slower than other
coastal provinces in developing the private sector. According to
official sources, the non-state sector accounts for less than 20
percent of the province's entire economy.
</P>
<P>
Local private companies have been asked to pay over 40
different additional levies that have not been authorized by the
central government, but imposed by local government departments.
</P>
<P>
However, the private sector is overcoming various difficulties
and, by the end of 1996, the province had 1.15 million private
companies, employing 2.34 million people. It also produced 51.6
billion yuan worth of goods.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, private businessmen have purchased or leased
34 large or medium-sized state firms and hired over 800,000 people
who had been laid off by state companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
