<HEADLINE> Italy Intensifies Fight Against Human, Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Italy's air and naval forces in
the Adriatic sea have been strengthened to fight illegal
immigration and drug trafficking, the ANSA news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Italian coast-guard service has sent a new fast cutter
which has a top speed of 45 knots to help intercept the motor
launches used by Albanian smugglers, the news agency quoted
official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
All the boats and aircraft in the Puglia tax inspection service
-- 10 in all -- have also been put on an anti-smuggler duty.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, Italian vessels intercepted three smugglers' boats
on the Adriatic. Two of them were forced to head off back to
Albania and the third was picked up on shore later after its
infiltration.
</P>
<P>
The captain of the landing boat was arrested and all the 16
illegal immigrants picked up will be repatriated immediately.
</P>
<P>
In a separative move, Police in Puglia said today they had
uncovered evidence of a rising trafficking of women and drugs
among the immigrant landings.
</P>
<P>
Most of the drugs involved in the new wave of trafficking were
marijuana grown in southern Albania, the police said.
</P>
<P>
Two Albanians were arrested in June in connection with the
trafficking and more arrests are expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
