<HEADLINE> India's United Front Remains Firm in Standoff with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- India's ruling United Front
on Wednesday night rejected a fresh demand from the Congress party
on the removal of three ministers from its government, lobbing the
ball back into the court of the Congress party, the local press
said today.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers belong to the Dravida Munnetra Kazagham
(DMK), a key member party of the United Front, which was indicted
of being linked with the assassination of former prime minister
Rajiv Gandhi by an investigative report.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party, which lends crucial outside support to the
United Front minority government, has been demanding the removal
of the three ministers as a precondition for continued support to
the government led by Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a letter sent by the Congress party President
Sitaram Kesri on November 20, Gujral rejected the demand on Monday
night but offered to talk with the party to seek a solution to the
political deadlock.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting of top Congress party leaders on Wednesday
night, Kesri sent a second letter to Gujral asking him to drop the
DMK ministers "immediately."
</P>
<P>
Barely two hours later, however, the United Front Core
Committee at a meeting late Wednesday night decided to stick to
its position on the DMK issue.
</P>
<P>
"We are as firm and as united as ever on the question of DMK,"
United Front Spokesman S. Jaipal Reddy said after the meeting of
the Core Committee.
</P>
<P>
The United Front was unanimous that its constituents would
"sink or sail together," Reddy said, adding that the front had
authorized the prime minister to formally reply to Kesri's second
letter at an "appropriate time."  
</P>
</TEXT>
