<HEADLINE> Investments Surge in Philippine Economic Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Total investments registered
with the Philippine Economic Zone Authority (PEZA) tripled to 152
billion pesos (4.5 billion U.S. dollars) during the past 11 months
this year from the same period last year, PEZA said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of new industrial economic zones rose to 26 during
the period under review from 19 established a year ago, according
to a report issued by PEZA.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic slowdown over the past four months,
companies located in the export processing zones increased
steadily, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The total number of companies registered with PEZA reached 85
during the period, and export receipts from the 85 registered
firms hit 4.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among these firms were Fuji Precision Phils. Corp. and Philips
Semiconductors Philippines Inc., with investments of 122 million
pesos (3.6 million dollars) and 1.3 billion pesos (38 million
dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Economic zones have been a major foreign exchange earner for
the Philippines during recent years. In 1996, exports receipts by
the economic zones reached more than 6 billion dollars, accounting
for one third of the country's total exports that year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
