<HEADLINE> Building Multi-Purpose Port in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, November 27 (Xinhua) -- After years of work, Tianjin
port in north China has become the country's second largest port
for energy transportation.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, the port has spent 4.2 billion yuan (506
million U.S. dollars) building an additional 10.5 million-ton
handling capacity and 19 deep-water berths.
</P>
<P>
It has built two oil berths for 50,000-dwt and 15,000-dwt
vessels. The port has also had an oil storage area covering
hundreds of thousands of square meters and can
handle 30 million tons of coal a year for 13 inland provinces.
</P>
<P>
The port also has specific companies providing cleaning,
catering, telecommunications, and printing services.
</P>
<P>
The port's growth has stimulated the development of Tianjin
city's economy and increased its ties with the world. In the
first half of the year, 42 foreign-funded companies in the city
had 384 million yuan in output value and 24 million yuan in
profits.
</P>
<P>
The port's bonded zone has investors from 67 countries and
regions, and from 25 Chinese provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities. It provides processing, storage, transport, trade
and many other services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
