<HEADLINE> The Caribbean Could Be Third Regional Bloc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARTAGENA, Colombia, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The secretary
general of the Caribbean States Associations (CSA), Simon Molina
Duarte, said today that the Caribbean countries could form the
third fully-integrated trading bloc in America by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Duarte spoke at a preparatory meeting for the third meeting of
the CSA Council of Ministers, to be held in the Colombian city of
Cartagena, which is located on the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
"I regard CSA as the third bloc in America, which will
contribute to a hemispheric integration, because by that time
there will be three existing blocs: South America, North America
and the Caribbean," he said.
</P>
<P>
The CSA was established in 1994 and started official functions
in July 1995 after ratification by its 25 member countries.
</P>
<P>
He said since its operation, CSA has set up a profitable
tourist area, coordinated countries to help natural disaster
ridden regions and implemented a program to enhance air and sea
transportation infrastructure in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Duarte also mentioned problems currently affecting the member
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Primarily, the crises in Caribbean countries are caused by the
lack of capabilities to contend with mounting globalization,
market openings and liberalization," he said.
</P>
<P>
CSA is comprised of 14 permanent members and 11 associate
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
