<HEADLINE> Senna Trial Verdict Open On December 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 26 (Xinhua) -- A verdict on the death of
Brazilian F-1 driver Ayrton Senna will come out after nine-month
war of words on December 16, a judge said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Judge Antonio Costanzo said he would retire to think over the
verdict after lawyers for Formula One team chief Frank Williams
and five other defendants gave their closing statements for
absolution.
</P>
<P>
Senna, a three times world champion, died during the 1994 San
Marino Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The bone of the contention was the weld on Senna's steering
column which snapped just as the Brazilian ace entered the
Tamburello curve, causing him to lose control of his car.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Maurizio Passarini made a sharp turn-around earlier
this month, letting Williams off the manslaughter charges with
three track officials shelved but refusing to absolve the two
remaining defendants: Williams' technical director Patrick Head
and former team designer Adrian Newey.
</P>
<P>
He asked the judge to sentence them for one-year suspension for
their "microscopic" error - one of the lightest sentences
available for manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
If Head and Newey are convicted they would have an automatic
right to appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Ready To Increase Crude Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is ready to increase
its crude oil production up to 1.5 million barrels per day (bpd)
or 200,000 bpd higher than its current production ceiling of 1.33
million bpd, a spokesman of the state oil company Pertamina said.
</P>
<P>
"It will be no problem to Indonesia's oil production if an
agreement to increase the production limit is reached at the 103rd
OPEC (Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries) conference,"
President Director of Pertamina Faisal Abda'oe said on the
sidelines of OPEC's ministerial meeting here last night.
</P>
<P>
"It depends on what OPEC will decide. If Indonesia gets higher
than its current quota, we will fulfill it because we still have
the capability to produce about 200,000 more barrels per day,"
Abda'oe said.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC meeting, which was opened here Wednesday evening, will
discuss the details for increasing the production quota despite
most of the members supported the proposal put forward by some
countries, such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Iran.
</P>
<P>
OPEC needs to set a new quota in anticipation of the growing
demand on the world market which is predicted to increase by about
two million bpd, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abda'oe added that OPEC member countries should also consider
oil prices so that the new quota would not induce the decline in
oil prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that oil prices were currently stable, namely,
between 18.5 to 19.5 U.S. dollars per barrel although it was
reported that OPEC's oil supplies were currently exceeding the
quota.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's Market Monitoring Committee (MMC) reported that OPEC
member countries's production reached 27.85 million bpd while
OPEC's official quota set in Vienna last June was recorded at
25.03 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
OPEC currently consists of 11 countries: Indonesia with a quota
of 1.33 million bpd, Iran (3.6 million bpd), Iraq (1.2 million
bpd), Algeria (750,000 bpd), Kuwait (two million bpd), Libya (1.39
million bpd), Nigeria (1.865 million bpd), Qatar (378,000 bpd),
Saudi Arabia (8 million bpd), United Arab Emirates (2.16 million
bpd) and Venezuela (2.359 bpd).
</P>
<P>
The OPEC meeting will last till December 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian, Polish Premiers Meet on EU, NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Romano Prodi and
his visiting Polish counterpart Jerzy Buzek met here today to
discuss Poland's efforts to join the European Union and its
would-be membership in NATO.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Prodi said Italy attaches great importance
to its relations with Poland as Italy looks at Poland as a future
member of the European Union and NATO, a communique from the
Italian Premier's office said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Buzek stressed that the new
Polish government was eager to further deepen the already
excellent ties of friendship and cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of government also reviewed major international
issues and took note of the fact that Italy and Poland want to
intensify their cooperation in all possible areas, the communique
added.
</P>
<P>
At a NATO summit in Madrid in July, Poland, along with Hungary
and the Czech Republic, was invited to join NATO by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Buzek met Pope John Paul II in Vatican City upon
his arrival in Italy at the start of a series of Europe tours.
</P>
<P>
Following his Italy tour, the Polish Prime Minister will travel
on to Brussels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
