<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Shortage Causes Regular Blackouts in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine is suffering regular
blackouts caused by severe energy shortage, Ukrainian Energy
Minister Alexy Sheberstov said today.
</P>
<P>
Power supply is suspended up to two hours per day in southern,
western and central areas of Ukraine, including large cities of
Lvov, Kharkov, Simferopol and Odessa, Sheberstov said.
</P>
<P>
Fuel reserves at power plants have fallen to a record low,
about 30 percent lower than the same period of 1996, the minister
said. Half of the plants have less than two days' coal reserves.
</P>
<P>
On one hand, the energy crisis is caused by residents and
factories who are unable to pay their electricity bills. The
arrears have so far gone up to 3.2 billion gryvnas (about 1.7
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the other, the International Monetary Fund and the World
Bank suspended a total of 2.8-billion-dollar loan for market
reforms in Ukraine's energy sector this year on the grounds that
Ukraine failed to cancel a 20 percent energy subsidy for its
residents.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's power plants have then almost no money on hand to buy
either Ukrainian coal or expensive Russian gas from monopolistic
traders.
</P>
<P>
"Factories stop operation because of electricity cutoffs, so
that they have no cash to pay the energy bills," Sheberstov said.
"Power plants receiving no payments from customers have no money
to buy fuels, so they generate less electricity. It's a vicious
circle." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
