<HEADLINE> Chinese Students Finding Jobs in Countryside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Eight Chinese students who
graduated from two-year college and polytechnic schools in Jintan
City, east China's Jiangsu Province, have found jobs in the
countryside and have become village leaders.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Jinhua, who graduated from Jiangsu Petrochemical College,
went to a remote village, Xiangtou, and was appointed Village
Party Secretary.
</P>
<P>
He drafted a three-year economic development plan for Xiangtou
Village together with other cadres immediately after he settled
down in a shabby office. "Becoming a village leader from a
two-year college student is an opportunity and challenge for me,"
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The eight graduates attended a special training course called
"How to Be a village Head" before starting their new jobs.
</P>
<P>
At the talent exchange market in August, Jintan set up a table
to attract graduates to work in the village. Twenty-four students
signed up and eight were chosen through strict examinations.
</P>
<P>
This recruitment drive is aimed at attracting high-quality
graduates to work in the Chinese countryside.
</P>
<P>
Among 400 village heads, 65 percent have a secondary school
education or lower.
</P>
<P>
"It is a dramatic change -- the students used to be very
reluctant to work in the countryside," an official said. "It is of
great importance for the students to be willing to work in the
places where they are needed most."  
</P>
</TEXT>
