<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Numbering System Aids Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- China's social security is
being overhauled, and work on the proposed numbering system should
begin next year.
</P>
<P>
Standards for the numbers are being drawn up by the State
Bureau of Technical Supervision, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
These standards will be public by the end of this year, said
Shu Zhongming, division chief of the bureau's Standardization
Section.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, Chinese citizens will receive their own
identification number for insurance, including medical and pension
plans.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, a person's social security number will be the same
as the number of the ID card," said Shu.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Security is now sorting out the ID
numbers.
</P>
<P>
Establishing social security numbers is an essential component
in China's social security reform, leading to a standard
administration system, a Ministry of Public Security official said.
</P>
<P>
China began reforming its social security system in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The present system -- combining social and personal
responsibilities -- replaced the practice in which State-owned
enterprises covered employees' insurance, even for the retired and
the redundant.
</P>
<P>
China's new social security system is comprised primarily of
four components -- social insurance, aid, welfare and
allocation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
