<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG PM Denies Corruption Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinean (PNG) Prime
Minister Bill Skate today denied corruption allegations against
him by his former adviser, saying that secretly filmed videotapes
televised by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) aimed
to discredit him.
</P>
<P>
The footage, made by Skate's former adviser Mujo Sefa, appeared
to show Skate authorizing the payment of 1,300 U.S. dollars in
bribes through his internal affairs minister, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) reported today in a dispatch from
Vancouver, Canada,
</P>
<P>
"Any fair-minded person can see that the episode is a crude
set-up," Skate said in a statement released Wednesday from his
hotel in Vancouver, where he had been attending the Asia Pacific
Economic Corporation summit.
</P>
<P>
"I am concerned that the Australian Broadcasting Corporation
should give credence to the feeble efforts of a blackmailer to
discredit the prime minister of a neighboring country," said the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"I am seeking legal advice and will be traveling to Sydney (on
Monday) for the mining and petroleum conference to represent my
country. I have nothing to hide."
</P>
<P>
He said he had been aware there would be an attempt to
embarrass him and Internal Affairs Minister Thomas Pelika after
"pathetic" attempts to blackmail him failed.
</P>
<P>
Pelika said that he and Prime Minister Bill Skate had been the
target of a crude blackmail attempt, AAP said in a separate story
from PNG capital Port Moresby today.
</P>
<P>
The ABC last night screened video tapes filmed secretly by
former government adviser Mujo Sefa showing Internal Affairs
Minister Thomas Pelika accepting an envelope allegedly containing
1,300 U.S. dollars to pay off the local media.
</P>
<P>
Sefa alleged that Skate authorized the payments and others
totaling 17,955 U.S. dollars to ministers and backbenchers.
</P>
<P>
However, Pelika told The National newspaper today that he
returned the money after consulting Skate.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard today promised to
maintain drought relief to Papua New Guinea and Australia's
commitment to Bougainville peace despite the claims against Skate.
</P>
<P>
Howard told reporters in Vancouver he had not seen the ABC
report but had been briefed on the allegations.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously they are very serious allegations, but that is a
matter for Skate to respond to," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said Skate phoned him last night to tell him the
allegations were going to be made.  
</P>
</TEXT>
