<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloth Tiger for '98 Stamp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications will issue a stamp which depicts a cloth tiger
to welcome the upcoming 1998, the year of tiger in the Chinese
lunar calendar, said today's China Daily,
</P>
<P>
The paper said China has a tradition of using folk handicrafts
as pictures featured on Shengxiao stamps, each carrying one of 12
animals according to the Chinese lunar calendar, to represent a
specific year in rotation.
</P>
<P>
Gao Qiuying, a village woman in north China's Shanxi province
made the cloth tiger, a traditional handicraft called Lihou
Tiger. Gao's cloth tiger handicraft was selected by postal
officials and experts from the ministry as a rough sketch for the
forthcoming Year of the Tiger stamp.
</P>
<P>
Based on Gao's handicraft cloth tiger, designers from the
ministry's Stamp Printing Bureau will design and further improve
it so that the cloth tiger will be able to be printed clearly,
artistically and beautifully on the upcoming Year of the Tiger
stamps.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Stamp Printing Bureau said bureau
officials and designers have contacted and visited Gao. All
copyright-related matters have been settled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
