<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Winds up Vietnam Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Victor
Chernomyrdin Wednesday ended his three-day official visit to
Vietnam, which is believed to mark a significant improvement of
Russian-Vietnamese ties.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin is the highest-ranking Russian official to visit
Vietnam since the Russian Federation was established in June 1991
following the collapse of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, he held separate talks with Vietnamese
Communist Party Chief Do Muoi, President Tram Duc Luong and Prime
Minister Phan Van Khai and exchanged views on bilateral ties,
regional issues and issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese leaders said the friendship and entensively
cooperative ties between the two countries have stood the test of
time and become "a priceless treasure."
</P>
<P>
They added that Vietnam has consistently viewed the former
Soviet Union and present Russia as a great country. The two
countries have left behind the period when they experienced
stalemate in their bilateral relations. Russia and Vietnam have
now entered a new stage of development.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said Vietnam is a strategic partner of the Russian
Federation. Russia will do its utmost to develop the friendly and
cooperative ties between the two countries in many fields.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Russia hopes it will continue to get cooperation
from Vietnam which is the coordinator of Russia's relations with
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two countries have held elaborate
discussions about bilateral economic, trade and scientific and
technological cooperation and signed a number of agreements in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said the two sides also talked about their
possible cooperation in military technology and Vietnam's purchase
of advanced Su-27 fighters from Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
