<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions to Focus on Aid to Laid-off Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Trade unions at all levels
should put re-employment of laid-off workers at the top of their
agenda, Zhang Dinghu, vice-chairman of the All-China Federation of
Trade Unions, said yesterday, according to Today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Helping address the re-employment problem is of vital
importance to the country's reform, development and stability," he
said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this September, the number of laid-off workers
exceeded 9.6 million, according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Federation sources said the figure is expected to increase as
technology becomes more advanced and in-depth reform of
State-owned enterprises takes off.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Jieping, another federation official, more
than 100,000 officials have set up contacts with 20,000
money-losing firms and 500,000 families with laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The federation has allocated 12 million yuan (1.4 million US
dollars) in relief funds to be distributed to poverty-stricken
workers during the Spring Festival next year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from financial aid, trade unions nationwide have set up
more than 1,300 organizations to train about one million laid-off
workers annually, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
In addition, trade unions have set up more than 300 employment
agencies in 100 cities, helping at least 300,000 find new jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
