<HEADLINE> Philippine Gross International Reserve Level Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' gross
international reserves fell to 10.126 billion U.S. dollars at the
end of October this year from the end-September level of 10.966
billion dollars due to the payment of foreign exchange debt.
</P>
<P>
The 840 million dollar decline in reserves was also caused by
the Central Bank's dollar sales, local press reports today quoted
a statement from the bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The end-October reserves level was equivalent to 2.5 months of
imports of goods and services, it said.
</P>
<P>
The latest gross international reserves, however, are still
higher than the 9.5 billion dollar level at the end of July when
the peso fell sharply against dollar among the currency turmoil in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has sold more than 2 billion dollars to fend
off speculative attacks on the peso since the regional currency
crisis hit the country.
</P>
<P>
The reserves level once stood at 12.24 billion dollars in the
first quarter of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
