<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Industries' Sales Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Eight of the Philippines' 14
major industries posted significant decline in sales for the first
11 months this year due to high interest rates and peso
depreciation, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing results of a recent survey conducted by the Federation
of Philippine Industries (FPI), the Business Daily said among the
eight industries were automotive parts production, cassava
planting and millers, and battery manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Automotive parts posted the biggest decline of 30 percent to 35
percent in the third quarter due to credit crunch in financing and
high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The oversupply of cars in the market due to trade
liberalization was also listed as a factor leading to the decline
in automotive parts sales.
</P>
<P>
Cassava producers suffered 10 percent drop in sales over the
past two years due to tariff reductions and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Battery manufacturers also complained of high interest rates
which pulled down sales by 20 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Other industries were not yet affected but they warned of
possible price increase if the regime of high interest rates
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
Local banks raised interest rates significantly in the wake of
the sharp depreciation of the Philippine peso starting this July.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
