<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6,000-Year-Old Ruins Discovered in China's Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered some ruins that date back 6,000 years in the central
part of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The ruins belong to the Yangshao Culture of the Neolithic
period, which had a well-developed agricultural system.
</P>
<P>
The find is considered valuable for archeological research and
an important contribution to the study of the origins and
development of Chinese agriculture and the movement of ancient
people in north China, archeologists say.
</P>
<P>
The ruins, which cover an area of 30,000-sq.m., is in Qinghe
County in the valleys of the middle reaches of the Yellow River,
in what is referred to as the cradle of the Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have unearthed a graveyard, 19 buildings, and 22
fire pits at the site. A large amount of pottery, stone items, and
animal bones have been unearthed, providing clues to the lives of
ancient people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Automobile Production Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Production in the automobile
industry of Chile grew 17.3 percent during the first 10 months of
this year, compared with the same period last year, the
Corporation for Production Support said today.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing of motor vehicles in January-October totaled
21,435 units, including 17,603 pickups and vans, 3,827 cars and
five freight wagons.
</P>
<P>
General Motors was the major auto-maker of the country, with
17,650 vehicles, making up an 82-percent share of the market.
</P>
<P>
Automobile sales have been up considerably in the past few
years with 38 percent in 1995 and 11 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The National Automotive Association estimated that some
170,000 vehicles will be sold this year, 5 percent more than last
year.
</P>
<P>
Taxes of domestic and imported vehicles sold in Chile are
expected to be 5 million U.S. dollars, a small share of the total
sales of 2.6 billion dollars in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The association said that foreign auto-makers have accounted
for a large portion of the Chile's market, which is jammed by
about 40 different brands, posing a great challenge for the
domestic auto industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
