<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade of Shanghai's Foreign-Funded Companies Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign-funded companies in
Shanghai, China's largest manufacturing center, had a larger share
of the city's foreign trade in the first ten months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show 12.7 billion U.S. dollars worth of
foreign trade, up 14.2 percent from the same period last year,
accounting for 57.3 percent of the city's total foreign trade
volume.
</P>
<P>
Companies that specialize in processing did 8.1 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign trade, up 30.8 percent from the same 1996
period, accounting for 64 percent of the total foreign trade of
the city's foreign-funded companies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-backed companies also had about 7.2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of imports, up 3.6 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Imported machinery products were down 18.2 percent at 1.8
billion U.S. dollars, while electrical product imports reached 1.5
billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 26.9 percent. Machinery
exports jumped 54.6 percent from the same period of last year to
2.7 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 49.3 percent of the total
exports of the foreign-funded companies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded firms did 5.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of
exports during the first ten months, up 31.8 percent on a yearly
basis.
</P>
<P>
Electric motors, sound equipment, computers, and computer
components, are popular export items for foreign-funded companies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade with Japan accounted for a third of the total,
with 2.17 billion U.S. dollars worth of exports to Japan and 2.3
billion U.S. dollars worth of imports, up 17 percent and down 1.1
percent, respectively, from the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the U.S., Hong Kong, Europe, and Singapore are the major
export countries and regions. Japan, Europe, the U.S., Taiwan, and
the Republic of Korea are the sources of most imports of
foreign-funded companies in Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
