<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Members Agree To Increase Production Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 27 (Xinhua) -- The member countries of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) have agreed
to increase their respective oil production quota, Indonesia's
Mines and Energy Minister IB. Sudjana said here last night.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached Wednesday at the opening day of the
OPEC's 103rd ministerial meeting held here, said the minister. But
the conference had yet to decide by how much each member country's
quota would be increased, Sudjana said, adding that the question
still needed further debate.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in production quota will of course decrease oil
prices on the international market so that it needs prudent
considerations to augment the quota," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
A delegate from a Gulf state said Saudi Arabia expected that
OPEC could increase its production quota from 25.033 million
barrels per day (bpd) to 27 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the United Arab Emirates and Kuwait hailed the
decision. The two countries however opined that the decision to
increase the production quota should be made through a compromise
among all OPEC member countries.
</P>
<P>
Sudjana also said that Indonesia alone was ready to increase
its production quota from 1.3 million bpd to 1.5 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, former OPEC secretary general Soebroto of
Indonesia said OPEC should provide the details of the amount of
oil production and the tendency of oil prices on the
international market.
</P>
<P>
Details of the production level would be decisive to the future
of OPEC as an organization which had the authority to govern the
oil trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
The 103rd OPEC ministerial meeting opened here Wednesday
evening. Delegates from the 11 member countries attended the
conference which will last till December 1.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the meeting said, the increase of OPEC's production
ceiling and the preparation for the Third Conference of the
Parties (COP) will be main topics during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
COP meeting will be held in Kyoto, Japan, next week.
</P>
<P>
OPEC groups Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria,
Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Venezuela and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
