<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Becoming Civil Servants in Eastern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Lu Yonggang, a civil servant in
a township government office in the city of Zhangqiu in east
China's Shandong province, is one of 41 farmers who have gotten
township government posts recently.
</P>
<P>
Only four years ago, 25-year-old Lu was a farmer. Then he got
work at a small cement factory and was sent by the factory for a
two-year education program because of outstanding work.
</P>
<P>
Then he decided to take the civil service exam, the first time
that farmers were allowed to participate in the exam. 3,226 people
passed the exam.
</P>
<P>
Lu said he had never thought of being a civil servant in the
past, but now says, "My example tells other people that as long as
a farmer improves himself by getting more education, he has a
chance of holding a government post."
</P>
<P>
Now, many of Lu's friends expect to follow suit. One friend
said he had not registered to take the exam because he had no
higher education, but he's applying to study in a correspondence
school. He said he'll take part in the exams after he gets a
diploma.
</P>
<P>
Township government officials say they believe the farmers who
have become civil servants were born in rural areas and are
familiar with rural conditions and are able to do their new jobs
well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
