<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, November 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CALGARY, Canada -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin
Wednesday said that he was looking forward to extensive talks with
Canadian leaders so as to usher China-Canada relations into a new
stage.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon hosted by Canadian Governor-General
Romieo LeBlanc, Jiang said he would discuss with Canadian leaders
bilateral relations oriented towards the 21st century and major
international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the luncheon, LeBlanc welcomed Jiang. The
visit is the first by Jiang as the Chinese president to Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Our citizens hold your country in great respect, and we share
with the Chinese people the goals of peace, prosperity, and
partnership in the future," LeBlanc added.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Wednesday that it was
confident its allies would be behind Washington for "serious"
military action against Iraq if it was deemed necessary by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I do feel strongly we will get the support we need when the
time comes," Marine Corps Gen. Anthony Zinni, the commander of
U.S. forces in the Gulf, told a briefing after a tour of the
region.
</P>
<P>
But the Arab world, disillusioned by U.S. pro-Israeli and
anti-Iraqi policies in the Middle East, has already rejected
Washington's requirement of using their bases to strike Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Kim Gye-gwan, vice foreign minister of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) held talks on
Wednesday with Charles Kartman, principal deputy assistant
secretary of state for East Asian and Pacific Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kim made no statement to reporters as he walked through the
State Department's main entrance, flanked by aides.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said Kim and Kartman, the most senior officials
of the two countries to hold talks here for the first time, were
discussing issues ranging from liaison offices to missing American
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
The meeting followed last week's agreement among the DPRK,
South Korea, the United States and China to begin peace talks for
the Korean Peninsula in Geneva on Dec. 9.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein Wednesday invited U.N.
experts to his presidential houses to make sure if there are any
weapons of mass destruction as alleged by U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Two representatives from each of the 20 countries that take
part in the U.N. inspection teams, and five experts or diplomats
from each of the 15 U.N. Security Council members have been
invited, involving a total of 115 people, according to a statement
by the Revolution Command Council.
</P>
<P>
But the statement did not specify the number of presidential
houses to be inspected.
</P>
<P>
These representatives can visit the presidential palaces "for a
period of one week or more, or for a month, so that they can find
out the truth," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The invitations were made after U.N. weapons inspection teams
said the presidential palaces are the likely targets for hiding
weapons of mass destruction, like chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
