<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Referee Strike to Stop Spanish League Programme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, November 27 (Xinhua) -- All first division soccer
matches this weekend in Spain will be cancelled because of a
referees' strike, a senior referee said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Many referees were angered by insults from players and club
officials after last weekend's first division games, which
included hotly-disputed penalties in several high-profile games.
</P>
<P>
Jose Lopez Nieto, one of the most respected referees in Spain
confirmed the news in an interview on the COPE radio station.
</P>
<P>
"We've had to put up with this for a long time...we have to
say 'enough'", he said.
</P>
<P>
Several Barcelona players and the presidents of Valencia,
Compostela and Atletico Madrid all made well-publicised criticisms
of referees over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Controversial Atletico president Jesus Gil and Barcelona's
Portuguese striker Luis Figo both grabbed headlines with their
comments.
</P>
<P>
"It seems we agree in this country that whoever shouts loudest
is rewarded, and it shouldn't be like that," said Lopez Nieto.
</P>
<P>
He said that the referees would stand by their decision.
</P>
<P>
"Much more tranquility is needed. After Monday we'll meet with
whoever is necessary." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
