<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People in Northwestern China Paying Less for Medical Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, November 27 (Xinhua) -- Do people really need to pay
several hundred yuan for simple cold medicine? Why can't a person
get a simple prescription if he or she refuses to have an
expensive examination?
</P>
<P>
These questions have been asked by people in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region who feel they've been overcharged by hospitals
and are beginning to oppose it.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Public Health in the region recently passed a
regulation dealing with these problems and effectively stops local
hospitals from overcharging patients.
</P>
<P>
It has asked hospitals to lower the ratio of income from the
sale of drugs to total income, and says that "except for the
pharmacy, no department or individual has the right to handle
medicines."
</P>
<P>
The regulation controls the use of quite expensive medical
equipment and imposes a strict ban on unnecessary fees imposed by
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
It has been praised by local people, and the hospitals in
Xinjiang have also come up with reforms to change their management
policies.
</P>
<P>
People's Hospital signed letters of commitment with 24 drug
companies and stopped doing business with companies that paid
doctors to promote the use of their drugs. Another hospital lower
the cost of certain examinations by 20 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more wards have been opened with more beds to
serve farmers, herdsman, and other people who might have financial
difficulties, and at least a thousand extremely poor people have
enjoyed free medical treatment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
