<HEADLINE> Hope Revives in Bonn for Tax Reform Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The German government today saw
new hope to push through its ambitious tax reform package after
the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) surprisingly
indicated that it would be ready to renegotiate the reform.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a parliament debate in Bonn today, SPD leader Oscar
Lafontaine signaled that his party would be ready to break the
tax reform impasse provided that the government also come up with
a reasonable compromise.
</P>
<P>
He also surprised the government by offering to cut Germany's
top income tax from 53 percent to 49 percent and the lowest one
from 25.9 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, German Finance Minister Theo Waigel said he
welcomed the SPD's readiness to renegotiate tax reform, but was
also disappointed that the tax cut offers made by the SPD were not
so big as sought by the government.
</P>
<P>
Waigel had proposed early this year to cut the top income tax
to 39 percent and the lowest income tax to 15 percent. But the
plan was categorically rejected by the SPD which said it was
socially unjust and would create a huge financial shortfall which
could not be offset.
</P>
<P>
Tax reform is one of the major initiatives launched by the
German government to boost investment and help cut the country's
record-high unemployment of over 4.3 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
