<HEADLINE> Jiang Looks Forward to Talk with Canadian Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CALGARY, Canada, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese
President Jiang Zemin today said that he was looking forward to
extensive talks with Canadian leaders so as to usher China-Canada
relations into a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon hosted by Canadian Governor-General
Romieo LeBlanc, Jiang said he would discuss with Canadian leaders
bilateral relations oriented towards the 21st century and major
international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the luncheon, LeBlanc welcomed Jiang. The
visit is the first by Jiang as the Chinese president to Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Our citizens hold your country in great respect, and we share
with the Chinese people the goals of peace, prosperity, and
partnership in the future," LeBlanc added.
</P>
<P>
About one million Canadians are of Chinese origin, including a
sizeable community in Calgary. Thousands of young people in Canada
are studying the Chinese language, according to LeBlanc.
</P>
<P>
Mark Rowswell, a young Canadian, master the complex art of
Chinese "cross-talk." He is better known in China as "Da Shan."
</P>
<P>
LeBlanc told Jiang that his visit "will further advance our
strong relationship. It is a great pleasure for all of us to host
your visit to Canada."
</P>
<P>
In reply, Jiang expressed his appreciation at the "significant
contribution" to the China-Canada relations.
</P>
<P>
"The past 27 years since the establishment of diplomatic ties
have witnessed a tremendous development of China-Canada
relations," Jiang told the luncheon, adding the relations "have
gained a sound momentum of an all-round development."
</P>
<P>
"China and Canada have also enjoyed good cooperation in
promoting Asia-Pacific economic cooperation and maintaining world
peace, stability and development," Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, a 21-gun solute wellcome ceremony was held
at the airport and red carpet rolled out for Jiang. The
picturesque city of Calgary is the first leg of his five-day trip,
which will also take him to Ottawa and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
"My current visit to Canada is aimed at deepening
understanding, enhancing friendship, looking into the future and
developing cooperation," Jiang said upon his arrival at the airport
here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang started his visit to Canada after taking part in the
fifth leaders' informal meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum in Vancouver on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The trip will also take him to Mexico. 
</P>
