<HEADLINE> US Sure of Support From Allies in Military Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that it was confident its allies would be behind Washington
for "serious" military action against Iraq if it was deemed
necessary by Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I do feel strongly we will get the support we need when the
time comes," Marine Corps Gen. Anthony Zinni, the commander of
U.S. forces in the Gulf, told a briefing after a tour of the
region.
</P>
<P>
But the Arab world, disillusioned by U.S. pro-Israel and
anti-Iraq policies in the Middle East, has already rejected
Washington's requirement of using their bases to strike Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan has told the United States the Arab
nations would not support any U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
President Sheikh Zaid bin Sultan al-Anhayan of the United Arab
Emirates today even said that the Arabs should forgive Saddam
Hussein's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
In his strongest bid yet to have Iraq readmitted to the Arab
world, Sheikh Zaid said a decision on reconciliation with Iraq
should be taken by a majority rather than by consensus.
</P>
<P>
Zinni made the above remarks after he met with leaders in Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain and other nations in the region, following
a brief visit by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright last week
with no result in her persuasion of Arab leaders to provide bases
for U.S. use in case there is a strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Zinni repeated remarks made Tuesday by Defense Secretary
William Cohen that there would be "no more pinpricks" if the
United States decided to punish Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. "serious" military action would "put at risk
the things that mean most to Saddam... things like the special
Republican Guards that keep him in power, his own infrastructure
and command and control systems and those kinds of things."
</P>
</TEXT>
