<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Warns of Boeing 747 Electrical Surges in Wiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration today warned airlines of possible electrical surges
in wiring near the central fuel tanks of some Boeing 747 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The FAA asked airlines to install new equipment to shield
certain wiring in the fuel monitoring system in some Boeing 747s
in the next 12 months and also called on airlines to immediately
inspect wiring in some fuel pumps in older Boeing 747s.
</P>
<P>
The FAA said the measures were based on recent tests by the
National Transportation Safety Board as part of the TWA Flight 800
crash probe.
</P>
<P>
Investigators have ruled out a bomb or missile attack and have
focused on the electrical system near the central fuel tank of the
Boeing 747 that crashed on July 17, 1996 off New York City. The
TWA Flight 800 exploded shortly after taking off from New York's
JFK International Airport, killing all 230 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
The inspections will involve wiring in the Fuel Quantity
Indication System aboard 167 Boeing 747 aircraft with U.S.
registry and wiring in the scavenger fuel pump in 196 Boeing 747s.
</P>
<P>
The FAA said the recent NTSB tests found higher than expected
voltage spikes were possible because of electromagnetic
interference in the fuel indication system wiring near the central
fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
Silicone insulation found during some inspections is prone to
deterioration from fuel used to cool and lubricate the pump
motors.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the TWA Flight 800 accident, the FAA called for
inspections of all Boeing 747 and Boeing 757 fuel pumps. Last
January it required reinspection and repair of wiring leading to
fuel tank booster pumps on Boeing 747s made before 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
