<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip issues here
struggled in quiet trading, but stocks were mostly higher today,
supported by some encouraging economic news and a calm day on
Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 14.17 points to 7,794.78.
after surrendering an early 37-point gain.
</P>
<P>
But broad-market indicators edged high as trading slowed before
the holiday weekend. The stock market is closed on Thursday for
Thanksgiving and there will be an abbreviated session on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 484.06 million
shares as against 571.16 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 0.82 to 951.64, the
NYSE composite index rose 0.33 to 497.31, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 5.46 to 1,594.50.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.25 to
428.16, and the small-company dominated American Stock Exchange
composite index rose 0.69 to 662.49.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street started the day strong after share prices rose 1.1
percent in Tokyo. The partial recovery from Tuesday's 5 percent
slide helped push Hong Kong and other Asian markets higher. In
Europe, Frankfurt's DAX index rose 1.7 percent and London's FT-SE
100 rose 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
U.S. stocks also drew a boost from the bond market, which rose
after a series of reports suggesting the economic pace may remain
moderate enough to keep inflation in check.  
</P>
