<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Reviews EU's Trade Policies in Past Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's single
market program and liberalization under the World Trade
Organization (WTO) have generally improved access conditions for
the EU's trading partners and increased exposure of the EU economy
to international competition and structural change, WTO stated in
its report on the EU's trade policies and practices published here
today.
</P>
<P>
However, despite progressive liberalization, there are still
significant internal obstacles to efficient resource allocation,
resulting in higher costs in some industrial and services sectors
with adverse consequences on growth and competitiveness, the
report points out.
</P>
<P>
The report covers changes since the last Trade Policy Review,
held in 1995. The report prepared by the WTO secretariat, along
with a policy statement prepared by the EU itself, provided the
basis for a review of the EU's trade policies and practices in the
WTO Trade Policy Review Body on November 25-26.
</P>
<P>
Average most-favored-nation tariffs on industrial products have
fallen from six percent in 1995 to 4.9 percent in 1997, and should
be under three percent at the turn of the century, says the
report. In agriculture, average rates, although much higher, were
nonetheless reduced from 25 percent in 1995 to 20.8 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Import protection and the use of contingency measures remain
significant in particular industrial sectors such as textiles,
automobile and consumer electronics, where high tariffs may
co-exist with intense anti-dumping activity, the report points
out. Agriculture continues to enjoy the protection of high
tariffs, with peaks in cereals, meat, dairy and poultry, sugar and
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The WTO report emphasizes that the review is taking place in a
period of policy development in the EU. Major changes are in
preparation, such as the movement towards economic and monetary
union, further enlargement, and additional reforms in key sectors
such as services and agriculture. These factors, together with the
perspective of continuing negotiations under the WTO "built-in
agenda", are likely to maintain pressure for further economic and
trade reforms.
</P>
<P>
After commenting on the EU's economic environment, recent
developments, trade policy by instruments, border measure,
measures affecting production and trade, trade policy be sectors,
the WTO report concludes that the EU's trade policies and
practices have generally evolved in a favorable direction.
</P>
<P>
This should benefit both the EU and its trading partners, the
report says, adding at the same time that the present transitional
period in European economic integration presents challenges both
for the EU and the multilateral trading system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Better Lawmaking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Lawmaking in the European
Union (EU) countries has made progress but a better job still
needs to be done in this regard, said the European Commission, the
EU's executive body, today.
</P>
<P>
A report, which has been adopted by the commission on measures
taken in 1997 to improve lawmaking in the EU, shows that efforts
made since the Edinburgh European Council in 1992 have borne
fruit.
</P>
<P>
The commission noted in the report that prior consultation was
becoming more frequent, the quality of legislative drafting had
improved, work to simplify and consolidate legislation was
continuing and it was now easier to gain access to Community law.
</P>
<P>
However, the commission said that law procedures should be
simplified further and it is calling all member states to
implement Community law more effectively.
</P>
<P>
It also called on its member states to strive for better
lawmaking in order to play an active part in the process of
improving the quality of legislation.
</P>
<P>
The commission also noted that the present commission had tried
to concentrate on political priorities since taking office, which
it believed had led to fewer pieces of legislation being proposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
