<HEADLINE> Saddam Hussein Invites UN Experts to Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein
today invited U.N. experts to his presidential houses to make sure
if there are any weapons of mass destruction as alleged by
U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by a meeting of the Revolution Command
Council and the ruling Baath Party, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Two representatives from each of the 20 countries that take
part in the U.N. inspection teams, and five experts or diplomats
from each of the 15 U.N. Security Council members have been
invited, involving a total of 115 people, according to a statement
by the Revolution Command Council.
</P>
<P>
But the statement did not specify the number of presidential
houses to be inspected.
</P>
<P>
These representatives can visit the presidential palaces "for a
period of one week or more, or for a month, so that they can find
out the truth," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The invitations were made after U.N. weapons inspection teams
said the presidential palaces are the likely targets for hiding
weapons of mass destruction, like chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the tension triggered off by Iraq's expulsion of
U.S. members from the U.N. weapons inspection teams earlier this
month could be further eased with the invitations.
</P>
<P>
The crisis which threatened war was defused when
U.N. inspectors returned to work last week after Russia's
mediation.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after Saddam's
1990 invasion of Kuwait could only be lifted after U.N. inspectors
verify that Iraq is disarmed of mass destructive weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
