<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Urged to Compensate Holocaust Survivors in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli parliament speaker Dan
Tichon today urged the German government to find a quick solution
to the controversial issue of compensating some 3,000 Jewish
survivors of the Holocaust living in eastern Europe, Tunisia and
Libya.
</P>
<P>
"It is a matter of justice, not money," said Tichon, who is in
Bonn on a five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Germany has paid about 100
billion German marks (55 billion U.S. dollars) to Holocaust
survivors in the West since 1949. However, those Jewish survivors
living in eastern Europe had been excluded from the compensation
programs during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
International Jewish groups have been demanding that Holocaust
survivors in the former East Bloc should also be eligible for
monthly German pensions of 500 marks (270 dollars), the same as
Nazi victims in the West.
</P>
<P>
Despite mounting international pressure, negotiations between
Bonn and Jewish groups have failed to achieve any major progress
on the issue so far.
</P>
<P>
A solution should be found quickly, because most of the
Holocaust survivors would have died in the next five years due to
their old ages, Tichon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
