<HEADLINE> Greece Not Satisfied With Turkish Experts' Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- Greece today expressed its
dissatisfaction with the proposals made by the Turkish committee
of experts on Greek-Turkish relations, saying that these proposals
did not change the situation between the two neighbors as it
stands.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that the Greek government would study the
report and decide if and how the process would be continued.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish experts sent a report to the Greek government two
days ago, proposing that the experts of the two countries should
meet on December 10 and each side should state the issues in which
they believed some rapprochement could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed that the establishment of
confidence-building measures begin at once.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reppas denied that Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis would meet with his Turkish counterpart, Mesut Yilmaz, in
Paris and said that such a meeting would be premature.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Simitis and Yilmaz discussed the bilateral
relations between the two countries on the sidelines of the first
summit meeting of leaders of the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Turkish committees of experts were set up in May this
year with the aim of reviewing procedural matters relating to
differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries have been strained for
decades over territorial disputes and the Cyprus problem, but both
sides have been trying hard to improve their ties since earlier
this year and no real progress has been made so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971127.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Aims to Boost Jobs Creation With Structural Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
structural funds should create or maintain about 880,000 jobs in
Europe's declining industrial regions until 1999, the European
Commission said here today.
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive agency Wednesday made the remark on the
structural funds programs approved in the beginning of 1997 for
the period from 1997 to 1999 in a press release issued in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The new programs all cater to the need of the declining
industrial regions for employment-intensive growth and sustainable
development, according to a Commission survey published on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the survey, EU Regional Affairs Commissioner
Monike Wulf-Mathies said, "The immediate priority for Community
assistance is -- and will be -- job creation."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner added that the EU was helping achieve this by
reducing dependence on "outdated activities, through a process of
restructuring and diversification aimed at developing a modern
indigenous business culture."
</P>
<P>
Under the programs, some 9,000 million ECUs (about 1,100
million U.S. dollars) is to be spent in the EU's declining areas,
almost half of which will go to measures to improve the growth and
competitiveness of industry and business, especially small and
medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
Around 16.4 percent of the total population of the EU lives in
declining industrial areas, the so-called Objective-2 areas,
according to the Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
